<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Trans-AtlanticChallenge     07-24 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trans-Atlantic Challenge,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proud Bird Takes Aim at Atlantic Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-man crew determined to break the record
for a trans-Atlantic voyage set off Sunday from New York aboard a
$6 million speedboat.
   Honolulu businessman Thomas Gentry, 57, and his crew passed
Ambrose Light just outside New York Harbor at 11:26 a.m. Sunday to
start the race across the North Atlantic to Bishop Rock off Great
Britain's Isles of Scilly, race spokesman Mark Jaffe said.
   The 110-foot, 11,460 horsepower Gentry-Continental Proud Bird,
sponsored by Continental Airlines, will attempt to cross the
Atlantic in less than 72 hours. The current record time of 3 days,
8 hours and 31 minutes was set in 1986 by Englishman Richard
Branson.
   Branson, who owns Virgin Atlantic Airways and several other
companies, set his record on June 29, 1986, in the Virgin Atlantic
Challenger II. It was Branson's second attempt at the crossing. His
first attempt, in May 1985, failed when the original Virgin
Atlantic Challenger sank 138 miles short of the finish.
   Crew member Jeffery Brown, speaking by radio-telephone, said the
Proud Bird had passed over the Nantucket Shoals about 3:30 p.m.
Sunday. The vessel was cruising at 50 knots through six-foot swells
and fog, he said.
   ``We'd like a little smoother seas,'' Brown said.
   ``Basically the autopilot is doing the driving and we're just
kind of cruising along,'' he said.
   However, the boat's size, speed and sea conditions were making
for a rough passage.
   ``It's not a comfy ride. There's a rolling and pitching motion
and when you hit these swells. You feel a few inches shorter and
like you've been punched in the stomach,'' Brown reported.
</TEXT>
