<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Communists     07-24 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Communists,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filipino Rebels Say Washington May be Forced to Send Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels said Sunday that
President Corazon Aquino has failed to lift the country out of
crisis and the United States may have to send troops to prop up the
government.
   The rebels, who have been battling for power for 20 years,
issued a statement on the eve of the president's state of the
nation address.
   Meanwhile, four soldiers, a policeman and two guerrillas were
killed in three separate battles across the country during the last
24 hours, the military said Sunday.
   The rebels said Mrs. Aquino ``cannot cover up the basic truth
that the Filipino nation remains in deep crisis, that U.S. control
and interference continue to fetter national development, that the
nation is being ever more polarized along class and political lines.
   ``Direct armed intervention by American troops is a distinct
possibility _ meaning a much bloodier war for the Filipino people _
should the U.S. imperialists judge that the Aquino regime can no
longer stop the general advance of the people's democratic
revolution and protect strategic American interests.''
   Copies of the statement were were delivered to news agencies by
the National Democratic Front. The front is an umbrella for 12
rebel groups, including the outlawed Communist Party and its
25,000-member New People's Army.
   The government gave no official response to the rebels'
statement.
   Mrs. Aquino is to address the nation Monday when Congress
reconvenes for its second session after a month-long recess.
   In the fighting, the army said that on Panay Island, 230 miles
southeast of Manila, communist rebels ambushed and killed four
soldiers Saturday.
   On Luzon island, one of three attackers Saturday shot and killed
a policeman as he left his home near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base,
about 50 miles north of Manila.
   Also Saturday, two suspected communist rebels were killed in a
gun battle after they wounded a Philippine constabulary captain in
Cabanatuan, 30 miles northeast of the base.
   The military said last week nearly 2,000 people have been killed
in insurgency-related violence across the country in the first six
months of the year.
</TEXT>
