<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Peru-Drugs     07-24 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Peru-Drugs,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eleven Killed in Battle Between Rival Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two drug-dealing gangs waged a gunfight over
control of the local cocaine trade, killing 11 people and wounding
dozens of others, police reported Sunday.
   They said the battle in the village of Dos de Mayo, 240 miles
northeast of Lima, began Thursday when a Colombian gang ambushed
Peruvians as they transported about 260 pounds of cocaine paste to
a rural airfield.
   The firefight lasted for several hours and at least six Peruvian
traffickers and five Colombians were killed, according to police.
Witnesses told police that dozens of people were wounded, but
officials had no specific figures.
   A Peruvian police patrol arrived in the area shortly after the
battle ended and confiscated the cocaine, according to the
authorities.
</TEXT>
