<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-SeaCollision 2ndLd-Writethru   07-24 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Sea Collision, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0674,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fishing Boat And Submarine Collide; One Person Dead And 29 Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with two bodies found; picks
up 11th graf pvs: Police officials...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered fishing boat with 48 people aboard
collided with a Japanese navy submarine and quickly sank Saturday
near Tokyo Bay, leaving at least three people dead and 27 missing,
police said.
   The 92-foot boat, chartered for a weekend fishing expedition,
sank less than two minutes after the collision, said police in the
nearby port city of Yokosuka.
   They said 19 people were rescued from the boat but a 38-year-old
man died in a hospital. Divers subsequently recovered two bodies on
Sunday, said a spokesman for the Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's
coast guard.
   None of the 75 men aboard the diesel-powered submarine were
reported injured, said officials with the Maritime Self-Defense
Force, Japan's navy.
   Officials said Sunday that divers located the boat at a depth of
more than 150 feet.
   Officials said about 80 divers and 40 boats were taking part in
the search.
   The Maritime Safety Agency spokesman said the cause of the
accident was still under investigation and captains of both vessels
had been called in for questioning.
   According to Japan Broadcasting Corp. television, the collision
occurred after one of the vessels swerved to the right to avoid
another boat.
   Television news reports showed the submarine floating on the
surface near the accident site with no apparent damage. A handful
of men on its deck and hull scanned the surrounding waters and life
rafts were lined along its top.
   Police officials said the submarine, the 2,200-ton Nadashio, hit
the fishing boat, the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru, Saturday afternoon
about two miles off the port of Yokosuka near the mouth of Tokyo
Bay. Yokosuka is 28 miles south of Tokyo.
   Capt. Yoshiaki Nishimura, a navy spokesman, told a nationally
televised news conference that the submarine was cruising on the
surface on its way back to Yokosuka after a training exercise in
the Pacific. The fishing boat, from the nearby port of Yokohama,
was leaving Tokyo Bay, he said.
   Authorities were still investigating the cause of the incident,
he said. Visibility at the time of the accident was reportedly good.
   More than 700 ships a day pass through the entrance of the bay,
Kyodo News Service reported.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who was attending meetings of
his Liberal Democratic Party in Karuizawa, returned to Tokyo after
hearing of the accident, news reports said.
   Defense Agency chief Tsutomu Kawara expressed regret over the
accident, the worst involving Maritime Self-Defense Force vessels
and civilian boats since World War II, defense officials said.
   It was the first collision in Japan between a submarine and a
Japanese civilian ship since 1981, when a U.S. nuclear submarine
hit a freighter, killing two people, Kyodo said.
   The mouth of Tokyo Bay is known for its congestion of military
vessels, including U.S. naval ships, ocean-going vessels, ferries,
fishing boats and privately owned yachts and sightseeing boats.
   Yokosuka is the site of a major U.S. Naval base.
   The submarine, built by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, was
commissioned in March 1984. It has two diesel engines and is
equipped with six torpedo tubes.
</TEXT>
