<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0681 07-24 1015</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0681,1036</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fires Force Evacuation Of Homes, Two Areas In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES 2nd graf pvs, `Residents also ...,'' now outdated;
SUBS 19th graf pvs, `Hundreds of ...,' to UPDATE with portion of
Montana wilderness closed due to fire, other details. Picks up 20th
graf pvs, `A brush ...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Stands for AM-Drought-Fires on AM-News Advisory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two areas of Yellowstone National Park were evacuated Saturday
because of forest fires in Wyoming, while residents of 20 homes
near Spokane, Wash., returned after the forest fire that forced
their evacuation was controlled.
   Fires also burned in California, Colorado, Oregon, Idaho and
Utah, and several large fires burned in remote areas of Alaska.
   Yellowstone National Park officials said Saturday the south
entrance to the park will be closed for several days. The Grant
Village Hotel and a campground in Yellowstone were closed earlier
in the day, and visitors and employees moved out as a precaution
because a fire had crept to within one-half mile of Lewis Lake.
   ``We had strong and erratic winds (Friday), a windstorm blew
trees down on the road,'' said park fire information officer Joan
Anzelmo. ``The same wind also kicked the fire in and had it moving
toward Grant Village.''
   In Idaho near the Wyoming border, 200 firefighters were strung
out along the two-mile-long northern flank of the North Fork fire
on the Idaho-Wyoming border that was burning mainly inside
Yellowstone, Targhee National Forest spokesman Bruce Fox said.
   Officials had worried that high winds forecast for Saturday
would aggravate the 600-acre blaze. But cloud cover kept both the
temperature and the wind from getting out of control, and crews
made progress on fire lines on the north flank, he said.
   ``We were anticipating it could double today if we got the wind.
But if we have another day like this, we might be coming close (to
containment),'' Fox said.
   Other fires in Yellowstone included the 14,000- to 15,000-acre
Clover fire in a remote backcountry area.
   Wind created problems for the 830 firefighters trying to contain
the Mink Creek fire in northwestern Wyoming that charred 21,300
acres in the Bridger-Teton National Forest and burned to within a
mile of Yellowstone's boundary.
   A containment line had been established around about 80 percent
of the fire's southern end, said Ed Waldapfel, fire information
officer.
   In southern Idaho, the Poison Creek fire in Sawtooth National
Forest southwest of Twin Falls was burning out of control Saturday.
More than 150 firefighters battled the blaze, which had charred
over 2,000 acres of the tinder-dry high desert since Thursday.
   Residents evacuated from about 20 homes bordering the Spokane
(Wash.) Indian Reservation returned home Saturday after
firefighters cut a containment line around a 2,420-acre blaze on
the reservation.
   However, officials were not yet calling the fire contained
because 40 percent of the material inside the line was unburned,
said Norm Anderson, a Wenatchee National Forest official.
   About 200 firefighters, including volunteers and crews from the
U.S. Forest Service and Bureau of Indian Affairs, used bulldozers
and hand tools to cut the line around most of the fire, with the
Spokane River forming the rest of the boundary, Anderson said.
   Anderson estimated the fire got within 50 yards of at least one
home. The houses were evacuated Friday.
   Also Saturday, a 1,500-acre fire at the adjacent Colville
(Wash.) Indian Reservation was contained, said BIA fire control
officer Pat Quill. The blaze was blamed on farm equipment operating
in high grasses.
   About 50 people who were forced from their homes by a forest
fire on the outskirts of Kalispell, Mont., were allowed to return
Saturday after crews managed to get a line around the 120-acre
blaze. No homes were lost although several were threatened.
   ``We only have one road closed, and that's to try to find out
where it (the fire) started,'' said Flathead County Deputy Sheriff
Phil Caperton. Authorities believed the blaze, which broke out
Friday, was man-caused.
   Hundreds of firefighters battled about a half-dozen other fires
in western Montana. Two fires were being allowed to run their
course because they are in wilderness areas, including the Canyon
Creek fire in the Scapegoat Wilderness north of Ovando. Authorities
closed about 75,000 acres of the 250,000-acre wilderness on
Saturday due to the blaze.
   Marcia Hogan, a forest spokeswoman, said the blaze grew
substantially Saturday but that no estimate on its size was
available because smoke obscured much of the area. Earlier, the
fire was reported to have consumed 2,000 acres.
   A brush fire about eight miles north of Canon City, Colo., grew
to 1,700 acres Saturday afternoon as about 330 firefighters and
aircraft battled the blaze in steep terrain on Cooper Mountain.
   Bureau of Land Management spokesman Ken Smith blamed the growth
of the fire on winds.
   ``The wind has changed directions about three times today, and
now it's fairly calm again,'' Smith said. The blaze, which broke
out Thursday, is named the ``Dinosaur fire'' because it is near a
fossil site.
   Before the Dinosaur fire, fires had burned about 21,000 acres
across Colorado since last weekend. The other fires were all
contained by Thursday.
   In Southern California, a fire sparked by fireworks was
contained Saturday after it burned about 420 acres of the San
Bernardino National Forest near Yucaipa, said U.S. Forest Service
spokeswoman Melody Fountain.
   And in Northern California, firefighters finally contained two
fires in Calaveras County after the blazes charred about 10,800
acres. Dick Craig, a spokesman for the California Department of
Forestry, said full control of the blazes was expected by Monday
night.
   Damage from the fires totaled $11 million, including timber and
property losses and fire suppression efforts, said Sharon Torrence,
a spokeswoman for the CDF in Rail Road Flat, 150 miles east of San
Francisco and a few miles west of the fires.
   Six homes, nine other buildings and eight vehicles were lost
since the arson-suspected blazes broke out Tuesday.
   Also Saturday, firefighters battled a 200-acre brush fire near
Flaming Gorge Dam on the Utah-Colorado border and several small
fires near Salt Lake City, authorities said.
</TEXT>
