<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 0531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Iran-Iraq     07-24 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iran-Iraq,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Diplomat Calls On U.N. Head To Halt Iraqi Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's foreign minister said Sunday that
Iraqi raids into Iran were a violation of a U.N. resolution calling
for an end to the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati called on U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to take ``timely and
preventive action'' to halt the incursions, Tehran radio reported.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Velayati left
Tehran for the United Nations on Sunday for the cease-fire talks.
   Iran said Saturday that Iraqi troops backed by tanks, warplanes
and chemical weapons thrust nearly 40 miles into Iran.
   Iraq said its aim was to capture a large number of prisoners
before the opening of cease-fire talks in New York this week. It
claimed it did not plan to keep Iranian territory and the Iraqi
News Agency reported Saturday that Iraqi forces began withdrawing
from the newly captured territory.
   Tehran radio reported earlier that Velayatiati had sent a letter
to Perez de Cuellar charging that renewed Iraqi aggression
threatened action on a cease-fire.
   ``Does the first article of the resolution not state that one of
the first steps towards reaching a solution is that of observing a
cease-fire and halting all military operations? However, Iraq has
not only not observed a cease-fire but has been conducting new acts
of aggression by occupying Iranian territory and has blatantly
violated this article,'' Tehran radio quoted Velayati's letter as
saying.
   A U.N. technical team planned to arrive in Tehran on Sunday to
begin working out details of a cease-fire.
   Iran announced on Monday that it was accepting the resolution,
adopted by the Security Council one year ago and previously
endorsed by Iran.
</TEXT>
