<1ST_LINE>r w BC-EmbassyFire     07-24 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Embassy Fire,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Investigating Fires At Madagascar Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two fires broke out at the Madagascan Embassy
early Sunday.
   Lt. Ransom Washington, spokesman for the District of Columbia
Fire Department, said officials were investigating a fire that
occurred at 2:17 a.m. EDT and a second fire that erupted about two
hours later.
   ``I smelled the smoke of the fire, so I decided to awaken my
family,'' said Leon M. Rajaobelina, the ambassador from Madagascar.
``We called immediately the Secret Service and within a minute they
were there, and the fire department was there within five minutes.''
   Battalion Chief Dennis Boatman, who was at the scene of the
first fire, said firefighters worked for about 10 minutes to bring
the blaze under control.
   Fire officials told the ambassador and his staff that the blaze
started in the reception area of the building. Jocelyn
Rafidinarivo, the embassy's counselor for public affairs, said the
fire may have been started by a lit cigarette.
   The fire department spokesman said he did not know if the second
fire occurred in the same room.
   No injuries were reported in either fire. Damage estimates were
not available.
</TEXT>
