<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 1128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GlennGould Bjt   07-24 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Glenn Gould, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exhibition Offers Intimate Look at Canada's Eccentric Musical
Genius</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He wore a wool scarf and gloves in summer and
lived like a hermit, communicating with the outside world mostly by
telephone.
   But when Glenn Gould died of a stroke nine days after his 50th
birthday in 1982, Canada lost not only a notorious eccentric but
one of its greatest musicians.
   For the first time since the pianist's death, an exhibition at
the National Library in Ottawa provides an intimate look at Gould's
life, from his checkered cloth cap to the room keys he collected at
hotels across the continent, including an entire set from New
York's Stanhope Hotel.
   Fortunately for posterity, Gould was a pack rat who set aside
one room of his apartment on Toronto's West St. Clair Avenue for
scores, scripts, letters, programs, souvenirs and assorted junk.
   ``He wrote everything down on pads. You can almost follow him
through each day,'' said Stephen Willis, head of the library's
music manuscript collection. The exhibit runs through mid-September.
   A packing list reminds Gould to bring Valium and Librium for his
nerves, and a TV Guide. A 1966 commentary for the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp. says in red ball point, ``Sometimes it seems to
me that Mozart has had a rather better press than he deserves.''
   A letter from his grandmother recommends a mustard pack for his
sore back, and Gould commiserates with an ailing Leonard Bernstein
(``Dear Leonardo'') by offering some tips on hypochondria. ``I have
several titles for diseases which I am expecting to have in later
life but have not yet had occasion to make use of.''
   After a piano technician dislocated Gould's shoulder with a
backslap, the pianist distributed a notice requesting that no one
offer to shake his hand. ``This will eliminate embarrassment all
around,'' it said.
   A Canadian celebrity at 15, Gould's international career had a
sensational start. He landed a lucrative Columbia Records contract
the day after his New York debut in 1955, and the first of more
than 100 discs, Bach's Goldberg Variations, is still rated a
classic.
   He suddenly abandoned the concert platform in 1964 in pursuit of
what he saw as a purer musical experience in the recording studio.
He eventually became his own producer, controlling a mixing board
the way a conductor directs an orchestra.
   He loved the microphone and dedicated much of his time to radio
and TV documentaries.
   A night owl, Gould rented a studio at Toronto's Inn on the Park
because it was the only place in town he could get something to eat
in the early hours, Willis said.
   The exhibit features Gould's favorite Steinway, his cluttered
pigeon-hole desk and the rickety card-table chair his father
modified as a piano stool. Gould preferred a low-slung chair so
that his fingers lay flat along the keyboard, the antithesis of the
pounding romantic style he abhorred.
   An animal lover, Gould left his worldly goods to the Toronto
Humane Society and the Salvation Army. The library was allowed to
purchase the collection of 20,000 items, packed in 226 boxes, on
condition it organize an exhibit. The display tours the rest of
Canada later this year, and negotiations are under way with U.S.
and European museums.
   The most personal documents were withheld, but Willis said there
was evidence of ``two or three relationships'' with women that did
not last long.
   In retrospect, Gould's career is filled with irony. He searched
for musical clarity and control in what he termed the ``backbone''
of a score and dismissed virtuoso playing and tonal beauty for its
own sake.
   However, he marred some recordings by humming along with the
music, a habit critics considered an affectation. ``Readers will
find the groans and croons intolerable,'' the Penguin Guide says of
one Bach recording.
   Gould preferred the piano to the harpsichord and played no part
in the rediscovery of original instruments and pitch that has
revolutionized baroque listening in the 1980s.
   He saw nothing wrong with splicing dozens of takes for one
definitive performance and envisioned an era when recordings,
adjusted electronically by home listeners, would entirely replace
public concerts.
   Gould holds an Olympian place in Canadian music.
   ``As a cultural symbol, he grows in stature every year, both as
a true Canadian original and as a certified hero of modernist
performers,'' said Robert Everett-Green, music critic for The Globe
and Mail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
