<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-USBase     07-24 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Base,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Form Human Chain Around US Naval Air Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HIROYUKI KACHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATSUGI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20,000 people formed a human chain
around the U.S. Navy air station in Atsugi on Sunday to protest
noisy night landings at the base.
   Three times during the peaceful, 40-minute protest the
demonstrators joined hands for about five minutes around the
10-mile perimeter of the base.
   Participants shouted ``Give us a quiet night!''
   There was no immediate reaction to the demonstration by American
authorities at the base.
   U.S. Navy pilots use Atsugi, 25 miles southwest of Tokyo, to
practice night landings, leading to frequent protests about jet
noise from residents of the densely populated area.
   Sunday's demonstration was sponsored by the Japan Socialist
Party, the country's largest opposition party, and by the labor
federation Sohyo and civic and religious groups.
   The mood was festive, and police reported no violence or arrests.
   Organizers said 27,750 people took part in the demonstration,
but police estimated the number at 19,000. Tadashi Abe, one of the
organizers, said more people showed up than expected.
   Noise from the landings has gone beyond ``permissible levels,''
Abe said, ``mainly because the base has increased its force.''
   The United States maintains military bases in Japan under the
U.S.-Japan security treaty.
   Last summer, 25,000 people formed an 11-mile human chain around
Kadena Air Base in Okinawa to protest the presence of U.S. military
bases.
</TEXT>
