<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines Bjt   07-24 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, Bjt,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bloodshed Brings Fears Of Breakdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grisly cycle of murders and
reprisal killings by leftists and rightists is raising fears of a
breakdown in law and order and threatening efforts to promote
democracy and protect human rights.
   ``Hardly a day passes without a murder or more being headlined
in our newspapers,'' the Catholic Bishops Conference of the
Philippines said in a recent statement.
   ``Our sensibilities are being battered day in and day out, with
reportage of killings and ambuscades, of slaughter and violence _
acts of terrorism all,'' the bishops said.
   According to the military's Capital Regional Command, at least
65 people, most of them police, soldiers and anti-communist
civilians, were slain in the Manila area by the rebel New People's
Army in the first six months of the year.
   Those attacks have led to formation of right-wing ``death
squads,'' which methodically target trade unionists, leftists and
social activists in an apparent bid to undercut their influence in
politics.
   Victims of the rightists include at least five Filipino human
rights lawyers. A prominent leftist university president, Nemesio
Prudente, has been wounded twice in two assassination attempts in
the past seven months.
   The violence is not limited to Manila. Nearly 40 people have
been slain this year in politically motivated violence in Angeles,
home of the U.S.-run Clark Air Base 50 miles north of Manila.
   Similar killings have been reported in Cebu, Bacolod and other
major cities.
   Several regional officials of the pro-government New Patriotic
Alliance have dropped out of the organization in fear since the
group's national chairman, Lean Alejandro, was slain last
September. The murder was not solved.
   Alejandro's group was among the social activist organizations
that rallied behind Corazon Aquino in the February 1986 revolt that
toppled President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino, who became president on the promise of restoring
democracy and human rights, has called for an end to the violence.
She warns that the unbridled killings will erode public confidence
in her government.
   But Mrs. Aquino's pledge to restore democracy has not been
enough to quell the 19-year Communist insurgency, which expanded
during the 20-year rule of her ousted predecessor.
   The killings underscore Mrs. Aquino's fragile control of the
police and armed forces. Military dissidents were responsible for a
series of coup attempts that rocked the Aquino government, and
leftists claim police and soldiers have been behind many of the
right-wing killings.
   Those arrested in a June 30 attack on Prudente include five
Manila policemen and a member of a government-backed anti-communist
vigilante group organized by police.
   Prudente, who was jailed under Marcos for alleged ties to a
leftist assassination team, had been accused by police of harboring
communists at his Polytechnic University of the Philippines.
   ``Their interpretation of democracy is some kind of police
state,'' Prudente said of his attackers. ``It's no different from
the communist society that they have been castigating.''
   ``We are one of those victims caught in the cross fire between
the extreme left and the extreme right,'' he was quoted as saying
by the Sunday Inquirer Magazine.
   Inability to curb the violence also threatens to undermine
public support for the policy of all-out war against the
communists, which Mrs. Aquino unveiled after peace talks with the
rebels collapsed in January 1987.
   Liberal Filipinos have begun to complain that the ``total war''
campaign is polarizing society and encouraging violence not only
against doctrinaire Marxists but also against those campaigning
legally for social and economic reform.
   ``The human rights issue calls for an urgent reassessment of the
counterinsurgency policy that has forced the government to trade
its humanist soul in exchange for short-term political stability
provided by support of the Armed Forces,'' wrote prominent
columnist Amando Doronila in The Manila Chronicle.
   Earlier this year, the rebels claimed they would scale down
assassinations because of the alarm the killings generated among
the urban middle class, which the communists hope to recruit to
their cause.
   But last week, Arnel Sandoval, spokesman of the rebel Alex
Boncayao Brigade, said killings would continue as long as the
Aquino government fails to curb the rightists.
   ``As the Aquino government continues to protect and refuse to
punish criminals in uniform, so shall the ABB resolve the bring
these people the revolutionary justice they deserve,'' he said.
</TEXT>
