<DOCNO> AP880724-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-LowRiver     07-24 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Low River,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>River Channel Straighter, But No Longer Moves With Easy Abandon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army Corps of Engineers' efforts to
tame the Mississippi are enabling barge traffic to scrape along in
spite of this summer's record low water and the river's natural
tendencies, Corps officials say.
   ``What the river wants to do is wiggle back and forth. What
we're trying to do is stabilize the channel,'' said Mike Robinson,
a historian with the Corps in Vicksburg, Miss.
   Strangled by a lack of rain, the Mississippi has dropped to more
than 20 feet below normal at Memphis and sand buildups have caused
traffic jams involving hundreds of barges.
   The Mississippi's flow is expected to fall to 20 percent of
normal at Memphis before the drought is over, and towboat operators
say they'll lose more than $60 million this summer because of
reduced traffic.
   On July 10, the Mississippi registered a record low of 10.7 feet
below zero on the river gauge at Memphis and the flow of water
rushing past the city was 115,000 cubic feet per second. Zero is an
arbitrary mark set at 183.91 feet above sea level.
   At what the Corps calls ``full bank,'' the flow at Memphis is
1.3 million cfs and the river measures 34 feet above zero. The
normal flow for July is 411,000 cfs.
   The record low flow of 78,000 cfs was set in 1936 when the river
measured zero on the Memphis gauge. Since then, the main channel
has been made narrower and deeper.
   In the old days when the river was left to wander, the
Mississippi often split into two or more channels and formed big
winding loops.
   In the 1930s and '40s, the Corps of Engineers cut off 16 of
those loops to straighten the channel and shortened the Lower
Mississippi by 150 miles.
   This year's low water has revealed stone dikes and huge concrete
slabs that Corps officials say are more critical than ever to
keeping the river open to barges.
   The dikes, sticking out into the water like long, skinny
fingers, force the Mississippi's main channel toward the middle of
the riverbed, while mile upon mile of concrete revetment _ a
blanket of concrete slabs _ keeps the river from forming loops by
eroding into the bank.
   The river can be more than a mile across from bank to bank, but
its main channel is often only 500 to 600 feet wide. The drought
has cut that to less than 200 feet in some areas.
   Narrowing the river and preventing it from flowing slowly around
a series of bends causes the main channel to dig itself deeper. In
spite of record lows, the Lower Mississippi remains 25 to 40 feet
deep in some places.
   But towboats are running into trouble at the so-called
``crossings'' where the river channel winds back and forth across
the riverbed. The current slackens and sand and sediment settle
out, sometimes putting the river at less than nine feet deep, the
minimum generally needed for barges and towboats.
   The Corps has identified more than 30 troublesome crossings
where dredging will likely be needed this summer between
Caruthersville, Mo., and Greenville, Miss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880724-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 1147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Dispute Bjt   07-24 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Dispute, Bjt,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Territorial Dispute Exposes Limits of Glasnost</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev moved away from quiet
diplomacy and got tough last week as he sought to resolve a dispute
over an obscure mountain region whose importance has grown far
beyond its contested borders.
   The Soviet leader's handling of the problem offers some insight
into how far he is prepared to go in allowing more openness and
giving people a greater say in how they are governed.
   Gorbachev said the struggle over Nagorno-Karabakh, a mostly
Armenian enclave in the republic of Azerbaijan, has inflicted
immense damage on perestroika, his reform program. He warned it
could doom his plans to modernize Soviet society.
   Addressing the Soviet leadership Monday at a special session of
the Supreme Soviet's Presidium, Gorbachev said: ``If we fail to
find the solution to this question today _ and we must find it _
this would have far-reaching consequences and would affect all
perestroika.''
   The immediate issue is the future of the sparsely populated,
largely undeveloped region in the Caucasus Mountains. The ethnic
Armenian majority set out in February to secede from largely Moslem
Azerbaijan and join predominantly Christian Armenia.
   But in the Soviet Union, a patchwork quilt of 15 republics
shared by more than 100 distinct ethnic and national groups,
redrawing maps is a dangerous business.
   Gorbachev and the Presidium, the top executive body of
government, served notice they were not about to open that
Pandora's box.
   Clearly, Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, is not a
guarantee of free speech as practiced in Western democracies, and
democratization does not sanction a challenge to one-party rule.
   The government has tolerated massive demonstrations _ including
some in the Armenian capital of Yerevan that have drawn hundreds of
thousands, perhaps even a million people, according to witness
accounts. But Gorbachev said redrawing the borders would constitute
an abuse of democratization ``fundamentally at variance with the
aims of perestroika.''
   Giving in to nationalist demands, he told the Presidium, would
``poison public mentality with nationalist venom and thereby spoil
relations between the peoples for many, many years to come.''
   In unanimously rejecting Nagorno-Karabakh's attempt to secede
against Azerbaijan, the Presidium warned that a series of strikes
that began in Nagorno-Karabakh and spread to Armenia, crippling the
local economy, had exhausted the Presidium's patience.
   The Kremlin authorized police to ``take essential measures'' to
end the strikes and ``activities directed at kindling national
strife and attempts to misuse democratic rights for anti-democratic
purposes.''
   Troops stationed in the strife-torn areas were reinforced.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan, a leader of the annexation drive who was
arrested in March on a charge of defaming the state, was stripped
of his Soviet citizenship and ordered expelled from the country.
   The state-run national press attacked strike leaders by name.
   First indications showed the new tough tactics were having an
impact. Most workers in Armenia returned to their jobs, although
the general strike continued in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   The central leadership clearly has acted with more restraint and
tolerance than would have been expected in previous Soviet regimes.
Not long ago, the Kremlin would have quickly turned to force to put
down the turmoil.
   This time, the Kremlin first tried the power of persuasion.
Gorbachev made a personal appeal Feb. 26 for ``civic maturity and
restraint,'' and the mass demonstrations in Yerevan subsided. But
two days later, a riot broke out in the Azerbaijani city of
Sumgait, and at least 32 people were killed, 26 of them Armenians.
   The Kremlin also tried changing the local leadership, installing
new party chiefs in Armenia and Azerbaijan. The new officials
quickly acknowledged that Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh had been
deprived culturally and socially under previous regimes.
   In March, the central government announced a major remedial
program to improve cultural and social conditions in
Nagorno-Karabakh, with much of the aid going to the Armenian
majority.
   But Armenians outside the region, perhaps encouraged by the new
latitude given them by glasnost, made annexation of
Nagorno-Karabakh a crusade. Those who died in Sumgait were its
martyrs.
   The legislatures of both Nagorno-Karabakh and the Armenian
republic sought the annexation, claiming the right of
self-determination guaranteed by the Soviet Constitution. But
Azerbaijan, citing another constitutional provision requiring
consent of affected republics before redrawing boundaries, rejected
the appeals.
   That set the stage for intervention by the central government.
   ``Democratic rights and the new conditions opened up and created
by perestroika are being clearly misused for anti-democratic
purposes,'' Gorbachev told the Presidium. Both sides, he said, were
using territorial claims to stir up national sentiments and
``conceal the really difficult, crying problems that had
accumulated.''
   Victory can only come by finding a common course, Gorbachev
said, adding that the search for that course must continue.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Katell, an Associated Press correspondent
in Moscow, has covered the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute extensively
since it began in February.
</TEXT>
