<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Democrats-Labor Bjt   07-24 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Labor, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leaders Confident Of Vote-Getting Strength For Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Booe, graf 7, cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bolstered by their highest delegate strength ever
at a Democratic convention, union leaders believe they can deliver
2.5 million votes for Michael Dukakis in November.
   Although the AFL-CIO will not officially endorse Dukakis until
Aug. 24, after the Republican convention, its political operatives
left here with no intention of waiting for what one called the
``pro forma announcement'' to begin working on Dukakis' behalf.
   An $8 million voter registration campaign _ put on a back burner
while unions concentrated on collecting convention delegates in the
primaries and caucuses _ is being reignited this week.
   After breakfasting with Dukakis last week, AFL-CIO President
Lane Kirkland said in an interview that unions will have less
difficulty than they did four years ago in getting their members to
vote a Democratic ticket.
   ``In 1984 there was a swell of support in favor of Reagan,'' he
said. ``We stemmed that tide better than the others. This year
there is an entirely different set of circumstances. There's no
incumbency and people want a change.''
   Despite the union label on 1,054 or more than one-fourth of the
Democratic convention delegates, labor still is maintaining a lower
profile in comparison with its all-out boosterism of Walter Mondale
four years ago.
   ``We worked harder in 1984 and all we got for it was fewer
delegates and more abuse,'' said James Booe, secretary-treasurer of
the Communications Workers of America.
   It was two of labor's more consistent supporters in the Senate _
John Glenn of Ohio and Gary Hart of Colorado _ who cried ``special
interest'' after the AFL-CIO endorsed Mondale in October 1983. That
was four months before the first Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire
primary.
   Kirkland takes satisfaction that both Hart and Glenn ``went down
the chute'' afterwards and that no candidate for national office
has repeated what he views as a slur since. But the scar is still
there.
   To provide Dukakis with a winning margin, labor leaders believe
they will have to get at least a 65 percent vote for him from a
rank-and-file membership that cast 39 percent of its votes four
years ago for Ronald Reagan.
   ``There is a mythology that it was the blue-collar workers that
brought Reagan in,'' said Kirkland. ``Sixty percent of our people
voted for Walter Mondale. But if we have to get two-thirds of our
membership, which encompasses a wide cross-section of the country,
to elect a decent candidate, it tells me there is a strong
conservative bias in the rest of the population.''
   The AFL-CIO plans to have at least 300,000 volunteers working
the polls on Election Day, said John Perkins, director of the
federation's Committee on Political Education. But first it has to
ensure that its members are registered.
   Labor political activists are working on a three-part formula
that could allow unions to provide enough votes to counter the
acknowledged more conservative views of the rest of the electorate.
It calls for:
   _ Voter registration that is 15 percentage points above the
national average of 72 percent. AFL-CIO officials estimate that
about 80 percent of the federation's 14.1 million members are now
registered.
   _ Turnout on election day that is 15 percentage points higher
than the 53 percent of the voting age population that went to the
polls in 1984.
   _ And a vote among union members for the labor-endorsed
candidate that is at least 15 percentage points higher than the
electorate at large gives him. The AFL-CIO achieved that in 1984
with the 61 percent of its membership voting for Mondale, compared
with 41 percent of the total electorate.
   With all three, Kirkland estimates trade union support of a
candidate is worth a net 2.5 million votes nationwide. ``That's not
something to be sneezed at,'' he says with pride.
   According to political directors for individual unions, the
effort faltered last time on making sure members were registered
and getting them to the polls on election day.
   Even though Mondale had an early lock on the labor endorsement,
many believed he could not win and support waned, according to one
labor activist.
   What's different this year is a belief among labor activists
that Bush has so many negatives that a strong union turnout could
provide Dukakis with the edge to beat him.
   ``Our rank and file by a slim margin voted for Reagan,'' said
Loretta Bowen, the Communication Workers' political director. ``But
they've indicated overwhelmingly they will come back to the
Democratic side. If George Bush were a warm individual, the fact he
has been a supporter of Reagan would help him. But our members
think he's arrogant and a snob.''
</TEXT>
