<HEAD>Robertson Says There'll Be No Friction Between His Supporters And
Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ex-Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson says Democrats will be disappointed if they are hoping
for friction at the Republican National Convention between his
supporters and backers of Vice President George Bush.
   ``We got what we wanted,'' Roberson said. ``I like the 1984
platform, and we're in agreement to stick with it.''
   Robertson, who pledged to campaign on Bush's behalf, attended a
Unity '88 Republican rally Saturday in Charleston along with Gov.
Carroll A. Campbell Jr. and Secretary of the Interior Donald Hodel.
   The television evangelist said Democrat Michael Dukakis was the
``most liberal candidate any party has nominated for the
presidency,'' and called the Democratic convention a ``carefully
crafted charade to make liberal Democrats look like moderate
Republicans.''
   Roberston also said there would be no floor fights on platform
issues at the GOP convention next month in New Orleans. However, he
did say he would like a plank calling for the nomination of
conservative candidates at all levels of the federal judiciary.
   ``We want judges who will interpret the Constitution as the law
of the land,'' Robertson said, ``not rewrite the Constitution as
the law of the land.''
   Robertson urged his followers to get behind Bush, predicting
they could provide the margin of victory in as many as 20 closely
contested states.
