<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 1215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MinkCreekFire Bjt   07-24 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mink Creek Fire, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Limited War Waged On Stubborn Forest Fire In Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MOSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloodshot eyes, a hoarse voice and a weary
demeanor are hallmarks of Rod Coleman's profession, a result of
working 15 hours or more at a time in the acrid smoke and intense
heat of forest fires.
   Injury or death are possible. The pay is marginal, an average of
about $8 an hour. Except for an occasional good meal, the only
benefit may be a shower after a shift.
   For more than a week now, Coleman has led crews battling the
Mink Creek fire, which by Sunday had blackened 22,650 acres in the
Teton Wilderness of the Bridger-Teton National Forest 40 miles
northeast of Jackson.
   ``It's just so dry,'' incident commander Dale Jarrell said
Friday. ``We just have to have some rain. But our weather people
say there's nothing in the forecast for at least 10 days, and we're
also facing the prospect of some dry lightning strikes in the next
few days.''
   Wind gusting to 35 mph and humidity as low as 11 percent have
exacerbated the dry conditions.
   The main thrust of efforts by firefighters _ as many as 830 but
down to 737 Sunday _ has been to prevent the fire from spreading
south, where it could threaten homes and dude ranches in Buffalo
Valley.
   The firefighters' line across the southern end was holding
Sunday, but the north end had burned about a quarter of a mile into
Yellowstone National Park. Officials said it was in a remote area
more than 30 miles from any major park attractions, but other fires
burned inside the park.
   The southern edge of the huge blaze was about five miles from
Buffalo Valley, but in between is an area of ``blowdown'' trees,
piles of tinder-dry wood left by a tornado last year.
   ``We're holding on at the south end, and every day we do that is
a real positive,'' said Jarrell.
   The lightning-caused blaze broke out July 11 and because it is
in a wilderness area, officials are required by law to allow it to
burn its natural course as much as possible. Such blazes are
usually allowed to burn until they threaten human life or private
property. In the long run, officials say, wildlife benefits.
   With the threat to residents south of the fire, crews have taken
a more active role. However, they are restricted in their digging
and cutting, and the use of bulldozers and mechanical tools such as
chain saws is discouraged. All work must be done by air or on foot;
there is no vehicle access.
   The cost of fighting the blaze was just over $2 million Sunday,
forestry officials said.
   ``Any wilderness fire is more difficult to fight because of its
remoteness,'' said Coleman, who has been fighting fires since 1968.
``The constraints make it even harder.''
   In addition to digging fire lines, crews deployed 20 miles of
hose to draw water from lakes and ponds. They also burned 2,000
acres to create a fire break on the southern edge.
   Coleman, 39, a U.S. Bureau of Land Management range
conservationist from Vale, Ore., said some firefighters have
experienced knee and leg problems because of the steep terrain. But
morale, he said, ``has been fantastic. These teams have a lot of
pride.''
   For the past few days, Coleman has been leader of a group of
Chippewa Indian firefighters from Montana. That crew just arrived
from battling another blaze in Lame Deer, Mont.
   The base camp has facilities for eating, sleeping, caring for
the injured and organizing the firefighting. Officials pore over
maps and infrared photographs of the fire area.
   Health and safety officials monitor fatigue among crews,
shipping some out for a rest and demobilizing others entirely,
bringing in fresh crews to replace them. A fresh crew could expect
to stay on the scene as long as 21 days.
   ``I'll be here that long if my legs hold out,'' Coleman said.
</TEXT>
