<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolReform Bjt   07-24 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Reform, Bjt,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reform Package Would Give Local Schools Autonomy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school system branded the worst in the nation
could become a trailblazer under a reform package that calls for a
slimmed-down bureaucracy and more neighborhood clout.
   The proposal calls for a council at each of the city's 594
schools to create a three-year improvement plan. If the called-for
changes aren't made, the council may fire the principal. The
councils will consist of 11 members _ parents, teachers, community
residents and the principal.
   Decentralization of power in public schools is a national trend,
but no district has given schools the kind of autonomy outlined in
this package, authorities say.
   ``Even though it's been talked about a few times in the country,
I think if Chicago goes ahead, it will be a unique step,'' said
spokesman Chris Pipho of the Education Commission of the States, a
Denver-based non-profit group that monitors school legislation.
   The reform bill for Chicago's beleaguered schools was approved
by the Legislature this spring and awaits Gov. James R. Thompson's
signature. Thompson must decide by September but has not indicated
which way he's leaning. If he signs, it will take effect next July.
   Critics say the measure focuses too much on administrative
reorganization and too little on programs to help boost performance
of the 430,000 students in the nation's third-largest school
district.
   Even supporters say that if the measure accomplishes all that's
intended, it won't cure deep-seated ills like the growing numbers
of low-income students, a double-digit dropout rate and teen-age
pregnancy.
   ``We'd be kidding ourselves to think that simply doing this is
going to do all those other things that affect learning,'' said
Michael Bakalis, dean of the education school at Loyola University
and the state's former education superintendent.
   But Bakalis, who co-chaired a coalition of community groups that
fought to reform Chicago schools, called the package ``a first
step'' toward eliminating problems that have given the system a
national reputation for mediocrity.
   U.S. Education Secretary William Bennett, who last year labeled
Chicago schools the nation's worst, has not yet studied the package
and is ``inclined not to comment until enough time has passed'' to
assess the results, said a spokesman, Loye Miller.
   The schools' problems stem largely from poorly trained teachers
and administrators ill-equipped to handle the 70 percent of the
student population from poor homes, said Ted Oppenhiemer, executive
director of the pro-reform group Citizens Schools' Committee.
   ``The fact is that children bring many more problems to school
than they used to _ health problems, language deficiencies, just
coming to school without the same kind of nurturing at home that
they had when it was a typical two-parent family situation ...
where children were talked to, where parents were very much
involved,'' he said Friday.
   He said the reform measure will help by permitting speedier
removal of unsatisfactory personnel.
   Also under the bill, a teacher could be dismissed after 45 days
for unsatisfactory performance, Berman said. Teachers now found to
be doing a poor job by the principal and a consulting teacher are
given a year to improve.
   However, the measure does not provide additional money for
retraining teachers or administrators, Oppenheimer noted. ``It's
fine to get rid of lousy teachers. But it's better to retrain ...
and teacher retraining takes money,'' he said.
   The package also would allow principals to hire teachers on
merit, without regard for seniority, reduce administrative spending
and staff at the city Board of Education and create a board to
oversee the changes.
   Many have mixed feelings about the degree of parental
involvement called for in the package.
   ``I don't feel that parents will have the time or the know-how,
nor the interest, to become that involved,'' said Francoise
Friedman, who heads a pro-reform group called Concerned Parents
Network.
   ``I am a very active parent ... and I know how difficult it is
to get parents involved,'' she said.
   The school board and the Chicago Teachers Union have declined to
endorse or reject the proposal.
   ``The entire bill is under review'' by the board's legal
department, said spokesman Robert Saigh.
   John Kotsakis, assistant to Jacqueline Vaughn, the union
president, declined comment. ``We haven't seen the final and actual
language,'' he said.
</TEXT>
