<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--AirportOutage     07-24 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Airport Outage,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airport Terminal Without Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electrical power went out Sunday at a
Detroit airport terminal, forcing Northwest Airlines customers to
retrieve baggage by hand and use stairs to leave and board flights.
   Intermittent power troubles began Saturday and worsened until
the power went completely out Sunday, Northwest spokesman Red Tyler
said from Eagan, Minn., where the airline is headquartered. He said
the airline was operating near its normal schedule from Detroit
Metropolitan Airport.
   The outage knocked out computers and baggage handling belts and
darkened restaurants and shops, Tyler said. He said many telephones
were cut off as well.
   Deputy Dennis Castille of the Wayne County Sheriff's Office
airport division said temporary generators had restored computer
service and some lights by Sunday afternoon, with full service
expected sometime Monday.
   Martin Bufalini, a spokesman for Detroit Edison Co., said the
problem had been traced to a Northwest cable and airline crews were
working on repairs.
   Baggage was being checked at the terminal curb and passengers
were getting on and off planes via stairways, Tyler said. Some
airplanes were using gates at other terminals, he said.
