<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clinton has decided to accept
an invitation to appear on NBC's ``Tonight'' show with Johnny
Carson, who has comically savaged the governor's speech at the
Democratic National Convention.
   Clinton agreed Saturday to appear with Carson on Thursday's
show, said press secretary Mike Gauldin.
   Clinton's speech nominating Michael Dukakis for president, for
which 15 minutes were allotted, went more than double that time.
The speech was criticized by conventioneers as too long and was
panned by commentators as uninspiring.
   Minutes after Clinton began speaking, television cameras
switched from the podium to delegates making slashing motions
across their throats and yelling ``Cut!'' Some delegates were
asleep. The biggest cheer came when Clinton intoned the words, ``In
closing ...''
   Carson mentioned the invitation Friday night. ``It would be
great _ we won't have to book any other guests,'' Carson said, as
his studio audience howled.
   Gauldin said Clinton discussed the invitation with his aides
Saturday.
   ``It's a neat opportunity. He thinks it will be a lot of fun,''
Gauldin said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale says he
wishes people would believe him when he says he just wants to
practice law and dabble in politics and international affairs, but
stay out of big-time politics and government.
   Still, Mondale says public figures should ``never say `never,'
'' and that's what gets him into trouble.
   ``I can't respond to these questions without appearing to be a
candidate, then it looks like I'm ducking,'' Mondale said in an
interview with the Star Tribune. ``Some people just can't believe
that a person who's been in office all these years doesn't want to
run for something.''
   Mondale, who lost the presidential election to Ronald Reagan in
1984, moved back to Minneapolis last year to join a law firm.
   ``I enjoy where I am. I'm with an excellent law firm and it
permits me to have a more civilized schedule,'' said Mondale, 60.
``You know, I've done 18-hour days and seven days a week for about
30 years. Both Joan and I want to work, but we don't quite want to
live that intense pressure-cooker life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was just a simple dinner for a few
employees, customers, suppliers and public officials _ 4,000 in all
_ but millionaire Curt Carlson dressed things up with Bob Hope as
master of ceremonies.
   And Hope, who got a standing ovation at Saturday's dinner,
referred to the owner of 170 Radisson Hotels, 150 TGI Fridays, 260
Country Kitchens and 700 Ask Mr. Foster travel service outlets as
``super Swede.''
   The event marked the 50th anniversary of Carlson empire, Carlson
Companies, one of the nation's largest privately held businesses
with annual revenue of $4.2 billion.
   Carlson said he wasn't worried about the estimated $1 million
cost of the party or the public's preception of it. ``We haven't
splurged for 50 years. We're splurging a little bit. It's worth
it,'' he said.
   Hope concluded by performing his own theme song, ``Thanks for
the Memories,'' with a twist in Carlson's honor: ``Thanks for the
firm you built, In '38 you planted the seed, And it has grown
indeed. You started out small, Now you own it all, Even the king
calls you super Swede, How lucky you were.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version of this item moved on sports wire</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankee legend Joe DiMaggio has
been discharged from a hospital 10 days after he underwent surgery
for an abdominal aortic aneurysm, his surgeon said.
   ``His prognosis is excellent. The reason he recovered so well is
that he's in excellent physical condition,'' said vascular surgeon
Manuel Sivina, who replaced the weakened section of blood vessel
with a Dacron graft.
   ``He did extremely well, no complications,'' he said Saturday.
   DiMaggio, 74, elected to have surgery after a routine
examination found that the aneurysm, discovered last year, was
worsening. The condition can be fatal if the artery ruptures.
   The Hall of Fame Yankee centerfielder and one-time husband of
Marilyn Monroe is due back next week for a checkup, but needs no
special drugs or diet regimen, the surgeon said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INTERLOCHEN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet pianist Alexander Toradze says
he's been playing for a one-person audience lately even when the
recital hall is packed.
   That person is his mother, Liana Asatiani, the first Soviet
mother allowed to visit a child who has defected to the United
States, Toradze said.
   ``Her presence helps me artistically,'' Toradze, 36, said Friday
while in town for a concert. ``It's not that I am not playing for
an audience. I adore American audiences. However, to give your best
you need this inner force.''
   Asatiani, 59, is accompanying Toradze on his concert tour, which
includes stops in Los Angeles, Chicago, Saratoga, N.Y., and Fort
Worth, Texas, before her visa expires in September.
   It's the first time they have seen each other since Toradze
defected during a concert tour in Spain in 1985. He now lives in
New York City.
</TEXT>
