<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     07-24 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burmese Leader to be Replaced Soon, Party Discusses Economic
Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special congress of Burma's ruling party
is considering drastic economic changes and may sweep away the
rigid policies of former leader Ne Win when it chooses his
successor, official sources said Sunday.
   The sources, who refused to be identified further, said the
changes being contemplated by the Burma Socialist Program Party
include lifting barriers to private foreign investment for the
first time since Ne Win seized power in 1962.
   The 77-year-old Ne Win announced his resignation Saturday as
party chairman, citing his age and indirect responsibility for
bloody anti-government rioting in March and June.
   By party rules, action must taken to replace Ne Win by Monday,
the final day of the three-day congress, which is being held behind
closed doors.
   Five other top leaders, including Burmas's president and vice
president _ positions less powerful than the party chairman's _
offered their resignations Saturday.
   Prime Minister Maung Maung Kha, the most senior member of the
party's 17-member Central Executive Committee who has not resigned,
was seen as a likely replacement for Ne Win.
   Like all members of the government and party, Maung Maung Kha
has been overshadowed by Ne Win since assuming his post in 1977.
The 68-year-old former army officer is generally not regarded as a
forceful or imaginative leader.
   At the congress' opening session Saturday, Ne Win called for a
popular referendum on one-party rule in Burma.
   In an announcement believed connected to the referendum, state
radio said Sunday an emergency parliament session would convene
Wednesday. Under Burmese law, only the parliament can carry out
referendums.
   The emergency parliament session also could deal with the
appointment of new government leaders.
   Sources at the party congress said proposals being discussed by
the more than 1,000 delegates included an almost wholesale pullout
of the government from economic sectors it once tried to manage
with disastrous results. These include agriculture, fishing,
forestry, mining, heavy industry, trade and transportation.
   The sources said the proposals also include joint ventures
between private domestic and private foreign investors, which Ne
Win steadfastly opposed.
   If the proposals pass, the state monopoly on both foreign and
domestic trade would end and the vast and currently illegal
cross-border trade with neighboring countries would be legalized.
   News of both the possible economic changes and the resignation
of Ne Win has spread quickly through this capital of 3.5 million.
But public expression of opinion was minimal.
   ``They (the government) are responsible for our poverty,'' said
one pavement hawker Sunday, echoing a sentiment heard among
small-scale dealers in city markets.
   Burma, potentially one of the region's most prosperous nations
due to an abundance of natural resources, sank under Ne Win's
leadership to one of the world's 10 poorest nations. It has an
annual per capita income of less than $200.
   Since October, student-led demonstrations have three times
rocked Rangoon and other Burmese cities, resulting in deaths, mass
arrests and the closure of universities.
   The October demonstrations were sparked when the government
withdrew several currency notes from circulation without
compensation. More than 100 persons died in rioting in March and
June, according to Western diplomats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
