<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DwindlingSchool     07-24 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dwindling School,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Town Recruits High School Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AVON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School officials are using newspaper
advertisements in an effort to recruit students from other
communities to pay tuition to attend Avon High School.
   ``I don't know of any school that is trying to maintain itself
by bringing students in from outside,'' said Peter Murphy, director
of the state Department of Education's district reorganization
efforts.
   Murphy said undersized schools usually collaborate or send
students to other school systems.
   The advertisments in the The Patriot Ledger of Quincy and The
Enterprise of Brockton tout the advantages of the school's low
7-to-1 pupil-teacher ratio, targeting students from large schools
in neighboring Brockton and Randolph.
   Avon, a town of about 5,200, is between the cities of Brockton
and Randolph, a few miles south of Boston.
   ``In a small school, the chances of individual attention are
greater and discipline tends to be stronger,'' Avon School
Superintendent Joseph Rappa said.
   Avon High's population has steadily declined from 700 students
about a dozen years ago to about 115 students in all four grades
this fall. For the school to continue, it needs to enroll about 35
new students this year and 60 and 80 more the following two years.
   Avon is asking out-of-town students to pay $1,500 annual tuition.
</TEXT>
