<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MoslemPilgrimage     07-24 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moslem Pilgrimage,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Pilgrims Sacrifice Sheep As Hajj Draws to Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Moslems on the annual
pilgrimage to Islam's holiest shrines Sunday ritually slaughtered
sheep on a plain in Saudi Arabia to commemorate Abraham's offer to
sacrifice his son to God.
   The ritual marked the end of the hajj, or pilgrimage, and the
start of the four-day Eid al-Adha, or Feast of Sacrifice, which is
observed by about 850 million Moslems worldwide.
   More than 1 million Moslems _ including about 1,000 from the
United States _came to sacrifice sheep on the same plains outside
Mecca where, according to tradition, Abraham offered to sacrifice
his son. He substituted a sheep at the last minute when God ordered
him to stop the human sacrifice, tradition says.
   The ritual sheep sacrifice followed a series of religious rites
that began Friday with prayers at Mecca's Grand Mosque, Islam's
holiest shrine.
   Later that day, the crowds moved to the plains of Mina, where
they spent the night.
   For the climax of the hajj Saturday, the pilgrims climbed Mount
Arafat, about nine miles outside Mecca, where they prayed, listened
to sermons and chanted.
   Before dawn Sunday, they returned to the plains of Mina, where
they stoned the devil by casting seven pebbles at three pillars to
reject evil, or Satan. The act recalls Abraham's stoning of the
devil to avoid being tempted into disobeying God's command to
sacrifice his son.
   Saudi authorities have built special slaughterhouses, where the
Islamic Development Bank killed the 600,000 sheep _ at a cost of
$75 each _ for pilgrims who didn't want to do it themselves. The
meat is to be distributed to the poor in Moslem countries.
   Some pilgrims will return to Mina on Monday and Tuesday to stone
the devil again. Others will proceed to the holy city of Madina to
visit the tomb and mosque of the prophet Mohammed.
   All Moslems are expected to make the pilgrimage to Mecca at
least once, if they can afford it.
   King Fahd, the official custodian of the holy shrines, and Crown
Prince Abdullah, arrived in Mina on Saturday to supervise the final
stages of the hajj.
   The hajj is being observed under tight security this year to
avoid a repetition of last year's rioting that left 402 people
dead, most of them Iranian pilgrims.
   Iran claimed Saudi authorities opened fire on the pilgrims, but
Saudi officials said most of the deaths occurred during stampedes
after Iranians held anti-U.S. and anti-Saudi demonstrations.
   The Iranians boycotted this year's hajj after Saudi authorities
announced they would restrict the number of pilgrims who could come
to Saudi Arabia.
   Information Minister Ali Al-Shaer announced the ceremonies were
conducted in ``peace and security.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
