<HEAD>Three Black Men Die in Violent Incidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black men were killed when a
group attacked a funeral procession with long, curved knives, and a
third black man was stabbed to death in a separate attack, police
said Sunday.
   In their daily unrest report for the preceding 24 hours, police
said the attack on the funeral procession occurred at Guguletu, a
black township outside Cape Town.
   The other death occurred in Sweet Waters, in Natal province,
when a group of blacks attacked a man in a home, police said.
   In other incidents in Natal, police reported: ``A gunman fired a
shot at a house in Nhanhlakahle, near Greytown, injuring a black
man; another black man was stabbed in Vredville, near
Pietermaritzburg, the provincial capital, when a group of blacks
attacked a house and set it on fire; and one black man was injured
when blacks stoned a bus in Claremont, in Natal.''
   The report also said that members of two taxi associations
fought in Soweto, outside Johannesburg, resulting in one black man
being seriously wounded and five arrested. Elsewhere in the
township, a group of blacks burned a private vehicle and a house
was damaged by arsonists, police said.
   No further information was given about any of the incidents.
Fighting between different black political factions in the Natal
townships has been going on for more than a year, with an estimated
500 people killed.
   State-of-emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest and a range of statements classified as subversive.
