<HEAD>New Soviet Envoy Named to Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet leadership has replaced its ambassador
to Pakistan with an official of the Foreign Ministry's South Asia
Department, the Tass news agency reported Sunday.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's parliament,
sent Viktor Yakunin to the job in Islamabad, Pakistan's capital. He
replaces Abdul-Rakman Vezirov, named Soviet ambassador to Pakistan
in May 1985, Tass said.
   The Presidium, or executive committee, transferred Vezirov to
other work, Tass said. It did not elaborate.
   Yakunin, who has been in diplomatic service since 1977, takes
over the Islamabad job at a critical time in the region. The Soviet
Union is withdrawing its more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan,
which borders Pakistan.
   The Kremlin has complained that Pakistan is violating agreements
providing for the pullout by supplying aid to the rebels fighting
Afghanistan's government. The Afghan rebels are based in Pakistan.
