<1ST_LINE>r i AM-VincennesLetter     07-24 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Letter,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wandering Letter of Support Arrives, Convoy En Route</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter signed by about 10,000 people
expressing support for the captain and crew of the USS Vincennes
finally reached the Persian Gulf on Sunday after bouncing around in
limbo for five days.
   The letter, actually a bulky package weighing about 50 pounds,
apparently went from San Diego, Calif., to Sydney, Australia and
then back to London before it landed here and was turned over to
U.S. Navy officials.
   In London, an employee of DHL, the express delivery service that
handled the shipment, said it was not taken off an airliner that
landed at Bahrain last Wednesday, and went on to Sydney. It was
found there and returned to London.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, said the letter would
be delivered to the Vincennes in a regular helicopter mail
shipment, probably on Monday.
   U.S. Rep. Bill Lowrey, R-Calif., sponsored the
signature-collection campaign last weekend to show support for the
Vincennes after its crew shot down an Iranian jetliner, killing all
290 aboard, on July 3. The Pentagon said the crew believed the
airliner was an Iranian jet fighter coming in for attack.
   San Diego is the missile cruiser's home port.
   One Navy source, who asked not to be named, said U.S. officials
were ``not overjoyed'' about the project even before the letter
went astray, because it drew new attention to the jetliner tragedy.
   A team of six U.S. experts is investigating the shooting down of
the Iran Air A300 Airbus.
   The Vincennes left the gulf four days ago after spending two
weeks at anchor here while investigators took depositions and
collected other data. Their report is due early next month.
   Navy spokesmen said the Vincennes is now in the Arabian Sea,
operating with the USS Forrestal's carrier battle group that
supports Navy operations in the Persian Gulf.
   It is due to return home in late August.
   The letter, described as hand-written on a large poster board,
expresses ``strong support'' for Capt. Will C. Rogers III and the
crew of the Vincennes ``as you strive to do your duty to God and
country in troubled waters far from home.''
   The signatures were on long rolls of paper attached to the
letter. The list was first reported to be about 570 feet long, four
feet longer than the cruiser itself. But Karl Higgins, an aide to
Lowrey, was quoted on Saturday as saying it was actually 1,000 feet
long.
   The 49th U.S. Navy convoy of the year was en route down the
gulf, with the missile frigate Nicholas escorting the U.S.-flagged
Kuwaiti tankers Townsend and Gas Queen, said a spokesman at U.S.
Central Command headquarters in Tampa, Fla.
   The convoy came a year to the day after another tanker, the
401,382-ton Bridgeton, struck a mine on the first upbound convoy of
Kuwaiti ships reflagged by the United States as protection from
Iranian attack.
   Iran accuses Kuwait of supporting Iraq in the Iran-Iraq war.
   The mining prompted a major buildup of U.S. and five European
navies in the gulf.
   The United States has about 14 warships in the gulf at present.
   Two vessels, the destroyer O'Brien and the missile frigate John
H. Sides, left the gulf for the United States on Sunday. They are
being replaced by the missile cruiser Reeves and the missile
frigate Vandegrift, according to U.S. military sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
