<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0737 07-24 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Urges New $2.2 Billion Child-Care Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf pvs, ``This is, with 2 grafs to CORRECT Wray
quote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, trying to
bolster his standing among women voters, on Sunday proposed a
wide-ranging child-care proposal that could give low-income
families government checks of up to $1,000 per child.
   The proposed program would cost $2.2 billion a year and
eventually apply to all families with children under age 4 in which
at least one parent worked, Bush said.
   Families who didn't get a government check would get a tax
credit, under the plan Bush outlined the National Federation of
Business and Profession Women's Clubs.
   At first, it would apply only to low-income families, and would
be phased in over four years to include higher-income households.
   Initial reaction to Bush's proposal was favorable, but tempered
with criticism of his overall record on women's issues.
   ``This is one of his first concrete gestures'' toward women,
said federation president Beth Wray.
   Asked how she would rate the speech, she replied: ``As far as
addressing our issues, he escalated on any scale. But as far as
addressing the kinds of things we'd like to see advanced, he didn't
come close to a 10.''
   After Bush's speech, many members of the audience chanted
``E-R-A,'' a reference to the Equal Rights Amendment, which Bush
opposes.
   The vice president said the tax credit, which would be in
addition to the existing child care tax credit and the federal
deduction for dependents, is designed ``to recognize the increased
costs of families with children.''
   There would be no strings attached to the tax credit and it
would apply equally to those who paid for outside child care and
those who didn't.
   ``As businesswomen, I don't need to tell you that child care is
a significant business expense,'' Bush told the audience, made up
of about 2,500 professional women.
   The certain GOP presidential nominee, who has proposed an
overall freeze on federal spending at the rate of inflation, did
not specify how his wide-ranging proposals would be financed.
   He was accompanied to the speech by former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, a frequently mentioned vice presidential
possibility.
   Mrs. Dole, wife of former GOP rival Senate Republican leader Bob
Dole, accompanied Bush here aboard Air Force Two, and, according to
Bush aides, helped worked on the final draft of his speech.
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate said that there was no discussion
during the flight of the vice presidential selection process. Mrs.
Dole spoke to the convention after Bush.
   Bush's criticized a $2.5 billion day-care proposal now before
Congress _ and favored by Democrat Michael Dukakis _ that would
provide direct government assistance to day-care providers. It
would not be limited to low-income families.
   Bush's child-care program included:
   _Expansion of the existing child-care tax credit to cover more
low-families, at a cost of $400 million a year.
   _Creation of work-place child-care centers for all government
employees, modeled after a program begun by Mrs. Dole at the
Transportation Department, and a federally underwritten liability
insurance program for private centers, costing $50 million a year.
   _More federal assistance to help states and local governments
set up programs such as sick child care and before-and-after school
care, at a cost of $250 million.
   Bush's proposals received polite, but scattered, applause from
the bipartisan audience. ``I'm not going to give you a political
speech,'' he declared.
   However, he told the audience that ``one of my attributes for
president is I did what many of you did _ I started a business.''
   ``The expanded role for women in the work force is dramatic. It
is the single most important demographic change in the second half
of the 20th century,'' he said.
   But still, Bush noted that women still earn only 70 cents for
every dollar earned by men.
   He said that, while this was up from the 59 cents of just a few
years ago, ``there is only one amount that women should earn for
every dollar earned by a man _ and that is one dollar.''
   Members of the audience cheered this remark loudly and waved red
purses, a symbol of the disparity in pay between genders. Bush was
presented with such a purse.
   Campaign aides depicted the speech as a major effort to
underscore Bush's commitment to issues affecting working women. His
campaign has been making a push to improve his standing among women
voters, shown by a series of polls to be a weak point for him.
   Republican analysts have said that part of the ``gender gap''
problem _ which also afflicted President Reagan in both 1980 and
1984 _ reflects voter registration breakdown: a greater proportion
of women are Democrats than men.
   However, some women's groups have accused Bush, as well as the
overall Reagan administration, of insensitivity to women's issues
and other social concerns and an overemphasis on defense issues.
   Asked why Bush did not mention the Equal Rights Amendemnt in his
talk, aide Deborah Steelman said, ``These are today's relevant
issues.''
   But Betty Forbes, president-elect of the organization, said,
``He may be beyond it (the ERA) but we are not.''
</TEXT>
