<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Talks     07-24 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Talks,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Secret Talks Held On Southwestern Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military officials from Angola, Cuba,
South Africa and the United States met privately on an island off
the African coast in an effort to work out a peace accord for
southwestern Africa, a news report said Sunday.
   The Portuguese news agency Lusa quoted a Cape Verde government
spokesman as saying the meetings occurred last week on the island
of Sal in the Cape Verde archipelago.
   South Africa's foreign minister, Pik Botha, confirmed that
representatives of the four nations met on the island Thursday and
Friday. He did not name the representatives.
   ``During the meeting, there was an exchange of views on the
military situation which will continue to be discussed in the
forthcoming meeting to be held in Geneva,'' he said.
   After U.S.-mediated negotiations in New York, the nations on
July 20 announced an agreement in principle for the withdrawal of
foreign troops from Angola and independence for neighboring
South-West Africa, which is also known as Namibia. South Africa has
ruled Namibia for 73 years.
   More talks are scheduled in Geneva next month.
   The Portuguese agency quoted unidentified Cape Verde officials
as saying that the talks there were mediated by Pentagon official
James Wood. It quoted the officials as saying the talks may have
been aimed at setting a timetable for the troop withdrawals and for
the implementation of Namibia's independence.
   In Washington, Maj. David Super, Pentagon weekend duty officer,
said he knew nothing about the talks or the possible participation
of Wood.
   The Portuguese agency, in a report from the capital, Praia,
quoted Cape Verde government spokesman Fernando Carrilho as saying
that the delegations were headed by Angola's armed forces commander
in chief, Antonio Franca Nadula; his Cuban counterpart, Gen. Jannie
Geldenhuys; and Gen. Ulysses Rosala Deltor of South Africa.
   Earlier, Lusa said the delegations were headed by deputy foreign
ministers of the nations.
   The report said Foreign Minister Silvino da Luz of Cape Verde
also was at the meetings.
   The talks are aimed at ending a 13-year war in Angola, where
guerrillas backed by South Africa and the United States are
fighting the Marxist government, supported by Cuba and the Soviet
Union.
   There are about 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola, according to U.S.
estimates.
   South Africa says it has 3,000 troops in Angola, but the
Angolans say the figure is 9,000.
   Cape Verde is a former Portuguese colony where Angola and South
Africa held their first face-to-face talks in the early 1980s.
   The latest round of negotations began in May. Talks were also
held in London and Cairo, with Angolan-South African talks in
Brazzaville, Congo.
</TEXT>
