<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugMortgage     07-24 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Mortgage,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Balks at Paying Mortgage on Seized House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is refusing to
pay off the mortgage on a confiscated $1.1 million home, arguing
that Republic National Bank of Miami should have known the house
was bought with drug money.
   ``At best for the bank, Republic stuck its head in the sand to
avoid obtaining the knowledge of the drug connection,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Alan Dagen charged in court papers.
   Republic seeks repayment on its loan to a Panamanian company the
government says was controlled by convicted smuggler Indalecio
Iglesias.
   ``If this is upheld, it could force banks to run FBI checks on
every borrower,'' said Stan Beiley, attorney for Republic.
   Under federal laws, the government may seize properties bought
or built with drug profits, or homes in which drug deals occurred.
The laws also provide that the government must honor mortgages or
liens on seized properties _ if the mortgage holder is an innocent
party.
   After the government seized the palatial five-bedroom home in an
exclusive Coral Cables neighborhood last month, the bank asked that
its one-year $800,000 mortgage be paid off when the house was sold.
But the government refused.
   Federal prosecutors contend in court documents that Iglesias was
laundering his ill-gotten gains when his Thule Holding Corp.
pledged its sole asset _ the house _ as collateral for the mortgage
in 1987.
   ``Of course, we didn't know anything about it. We had no idea,''
Republic President Frederick de la Mata told The Miami Herald
Sunday.
   No charges are pending against Iglesias, although he was
convicted of smuggling marijuana in 1981.
   The government says Republic should have guessed a drug
connection existed.
   ``Despite suspicious circumstances, Republic looked the other
way while accepting gratuities from Iglesias,'' the government says
in court papers, which allege the house was built using the
millions of dollars Iglesias earned smuggling drugs from 1980 to
1985.
   Thule allegedly paid for airplane tickets and a hotel room for
de la Mata's son's honeymoon only three days after the $800,000
mortgage was approved in a hastily called meeting of Republic's
loan committee. De la Mata contends that Ramon Puentes, an old
customer with no connection to Thule, gave his son the trip.
   The government also says the bank should have been suspicious in
part because de la Mata knew Thule was trying to sell the house.
Also, granting the mortgage in just two weeks was unusual, as was
granting a loan when the house was vacant, something banks rarely
do, court papers say.
   Bank attorneys say the government hasn't proved that Iglesias
was involved in smuggling in 1985, when the house was built, or
that drug profits were used.
</TEXT>
