<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     07-24 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kabul Hit by Rockets, Pakistani Village Shelled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heavy barrage of rockets on Sunday
slammed into the southern edge of the Afghan capital, hitting Kabul
Airport, a Western diplomat said. Newspapers reported the shelling
of a Pakistani border village.
   Pakistani daily newspapers reported Sunday that six people were
killed and 21 injured when the Afghan army shelled the border
village of Chaman, in southwestern Pakistan, on Saturday.
   One newspaper report said the Pakistani army returned fire. The
Pakistani government made no immediate comment on that report.
   No immediate word of casualties was given after Sunday's rocket
attack on Kabul, blamed on anti-government guerrillas.
   The diplomat's report followed near-daily rocket attacks blamed
on the guerrillas. During the past three weeks, 130 rockets have
blasted the capital, killing 80 people and injuring more than 100,
state-run Radio Kabul said Sunday.
   The latest attack also came after Pakistan accused the Soviet
Union of bringing troops back into Afghanistan to shore up
struggling government forces around Kabul. The Soviets have agreed
to withdraw all of their estimated 115,000 troops by Feb. 15,
leaving 50,000 government soldiers to fight about 200,000
Pakistani-backed guerrillas.
   The Western diplomat in Pakistan, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, also said at least four people died in a late-night
rocket attack on Kabul Friday.
   During an address on Radio Kabul on Sunday to mark the Islamic
holiday of Eid al-Adha, Afghan President Najib said another rocket
attack Saturday killed several people.
   He blamed the attack on Afghan guerrillas who have been fighting
the communist government in Kabul for the past 10 years.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, also reported four people
were killed and nine injured when rockets blasted the eastern city
of Jalalabad on Friday.
   Chaman, where Pakistan newspapers reported the shelling, lies
about five miles from the Afghan town of Spinbuldak, which rebels
had surrounding.
   Quoting official sources, a Pakistani opposition paper, The
Frontier Post, said Pakistan army troops returned fire.
   Najib said the Soviet troop withdrawal, provided for in an
accord in April, was progressing, but he said stepped-up guerrilla
attacks were ``obstructing'' it. He did not elaborate.
   The Soviet Union denied Pakistani President Zia ul-Haq's charge
that the troop withdrawal had stopped and 10,000 soldiers were
recalled from the Soviet Union to prop up the defense of Kabul,
Radio Kabul said.
   Quoting Soviet Chief of Staff Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, Radio
Kabul said Sunday that 35,000 troops have left Afghanistan.
Akhromeyev said half of an estimated 115,000 troops will be out by
Aug. 15.
   Meanwhile, another Soviet military officer, breaking with
Moscow's official line, said he doubted the Afghan army can survive
after Soviet troops leave. He predicted Islamic fundamentalists
will gain power.
   Maj. Gen. Kim M. Tsagolov, who served as a Soviet adviser to
Afghan troops, also told the weekly Ogonyok magazine in its July 30
issue that Afghanistan's governing party is hopelessly disorganized
and has bungled opportunities to make peace with insurgents.
</TEXT>
