<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan Returns, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0769,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede SANTA BARBARA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vacation Over, President Faces Drought, Nicaragua, Political
Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Refocuses first graf; restores last 7 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan returned to the nation's
capital Sunday after a week-long vacation at his mountaintop ranch
north in California and prepared to deal with the drought, aid to
Nicaraguan rebels and the fall political campaign.
   The president and first lady Nancy Reagan were joined on the
trip back to Washington aboard Air Force One by Secretary of the
Treasury James A. Baker III.
   Baker spoke Saturday night at a fund-raising reception in Los
Angeles for the re-election campaign of Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   An administration official dismissed speculation that Baker's
presence signaled any immediate announcement of his resignation to
run Vice President George Bush's presidential campaign.
   ``Essentially he is hitching a ride,'' the official said,
speaking on condition he not be identified. . ``The fund-raiser had
been scheduled for some time and he is hitching a ride back on Air
Force One.''
   Another official, speaking on the same condition, said an
announcement of Baker's plans is expected early in August. Bush is
as near certainty as can be to win the Republican presidential
nomination at the GOP convention that opens in New Orleans Aug. 15.
   On board Air Force One en route to Washington, reporters asked
presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater about Baker's plans and
were told he did not know, that Reagan and Baker had only a ``very
brief chat. They chatted in the hallway.''
   ``He's still treasury secretary, put it that way,'' said
Fitzwater.
   When reporters sent Baker a note asking them to come back and
talk to them about the question, he replied with a note in a folder
that contained a dollar bill. Baker wrote, ``Please note the title
under the signature.''
   The title under Baker's signature on currency is secretary of
the treasury.
   Leaving the airplane at Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland, a
reporter asked Baker, ``Can you share the news with us?'' He
replied, ``There's no news to share.''
   The president has summoned Republican congressional leaders to
the White House on Tuesday for a meeting that officials say will
focus on plans for the remaining six months of the Reagan
presidency, including discussions of assistance for the rebels
against Nicaragua's Marxist-led government.
   Kenneth M. Duberstein, the president's chief of staff, told
reporters in Santa Barbara that in addition to the congressional
leadership meeting, he will be consulting with administration
officials and Reagan supporters outside government during the week
to develop ``plans and strategies to get things done.''
   Fitzwater said Secretary of Agriculture Richard Lyng will report
to the president during the week on a trip of 10 drought-stricken
states that he and other government officials have completed.
   Also coming up during the week is a midyear review of the
budget. Fitzwater said he did not think it would affect the
availability of funds for drought relief.
   Fitzwater said Reagan is committed to making at least two
campaign trips a week on behalf of Republican candidates after
September, would speak at two Republican fund-raising events in Los
Angeles while in California for another ranch vacation next month
and might make at least one campaign appearance before he leaves
for the New orleans convention on Aug. 14.
   The president devoted his weekly radio address Saturday to an
attack on the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta, where he
said speakers repeated ``the same sad song they sang four years
ago.''
   He did not, as he had in some speeches, specifically attack
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, nor did he mention
Bush, whom he has often lavishly praised.
   The vice president will have lunch with the president on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
