<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over Midwest, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Sunday over parts of the drought-plagued
Upper Midwest, and parts of the Northeast got heavy rain before
unsettled weather moved off the Atlantic Coast.
   A cold front extending from northeastern Minnesota to western
Kansas triggered scattered thunderstorms over northern Iowa and
central Wisconsin.
   A strong thunderstorm moved through the area of the area of
Oshkosh, Wis., with wind gusting to 65 mph.
   Showers were scattered over the upper Ohio Valley and the lower
Great Lakes region.
   Much of the rain that had plagued parts of the Atlantic Coast
for several days moved off the Coast after leaving heavy 24-hour
rain amounts, including more than 4 inches at Putnam, Conn., the
National Weather Service said. In Massachusetts, more than 2 inches
of rain fell in a 6-hour period early Sunday.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered over eastern
Colorado, northern New Mexico, Oklahoma and northern Texas.
   And thunderstorms, some with locally heavy rain, were scattered
over Florida.
   Monroe, La., posted a record low temperature Sunday morning of
63 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 60
degrees at Arcata and Crescent City, Calif., to 106 at Needles,
Calif. Sunday morning's low was 36 at Jackson, Wyo.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over Florida, the coast of North Carolina and New England, and also
ahead of a cold front over Michigan, eastern Wisconsin, Illinois,
Indiana, the lower Missouri Valley and Oklahoma. Scattered
thunderstorms were forecast over eastern Colorado and widely
scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast over northeastern
Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted from Maine to northern Wisconsin
and northeastern Minnesota; in the 70s and 80s along the Pacific
Coast; in the 80s over the northern and central Plains, across most
of the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, the Ohio Valley and
from the Carolinas and the middle Atlantic Coast states to southern
sections of New England; between 100 and 105 from northern
California to western Idaho; between 100 and 115 over the desert
Southwest and the valleys of California; and in the 90s over most
of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
