<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-24 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0770,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill To Arabs In West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS one graf for 10th pvs, East Jerusalem ... to CORRECT
status of territory. Pickup 11th pvs, Moslems prayed ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed two Palestinians during
fighting in the occupied West Bank Sunday and 1,500 policemen
patrolled Jerusalem to prevent battles between Moslems and Jews
celebrating religious observances.
   Police blocked right-wing Jewish extremists from marching
through the Arab quarter of Jerusalem's Old City and arrested two
Israelis.
   Reinforced police were stationed in Jerusalam to prevent trouble
on the coinciding Jewish and Moslem holidays centered on the Temple
Mount.
   In the West Bank town of Qabatiya, Israeli troops shot and
killed one Palestinian and wounded three others, the army said
without identifying the victims. Israel army radio said one Israeli
military officer was injured during the clash.
   A Palestinian died at Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital after being
shot at least twice during a demonstration in the West Bank town of
Beit Jala, the army and hospital officials said. The hospital
sources said the 38-year-old man tried to throw a brick at Israeli
soldiers.
   The deaths raised to 233 the known number of Palestinians killed
since they began an uprising Dec. 8. in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and the Gaza Strip. Four Israelis also have been slain in the
violence.
   In the Gaza Strip, 25 Palestinians were wounded by beatings by
Israeli troops or by rubber bullets fired by the soldiers during a
series of clashes, Gaza hospital officials said.
   The army imposed or extended curfews on eight cities and refugee
camps in Gaza and the West Bank, confining about 250,000
Palestinians to their homes.
   Increased police security was mounted in the Old City, the
walled section of Arab east Jeruslem, as Moslems and Jews
celebrated major ceremonies.
   Israel captured east Jerusalem, the West Bank and the Gaza Strip
after the 1967 Middle East War. It later annexed east Jerusalem.
   Moslems prayed on the Temple Mount to mark Eid al-Ahda, or the
``Feast of Sacrifice,'' which commemorates Abraham's preparations
to sacrifice his son at God's instructions. At the last moment the
son was spared and instead a sheep was sacrificed.
   Jews marked Tisha B'Av, the anniversary or the destruction by
Roman troops of the Holy Jewish Temple about 2,000 years ago.
   More than 100 Jewish militants who demand Israeli control over
the Temple Mount held a prayer vigil at its gates but were barred
by police from entering. Jews can visit the area individually but
under an arrangement with Moslem religious authorities they are not
allowed to pray on the Temple Mount.
   Police later barred the group from entering the adjacent Moslem
quarter after they refused to abandon the Israeli flags they were
carrying.
   But about 20 followers of the right-wing Tehiya Party and the
militantly anti-Arab Kach movement managed to slip through the
police lines and marched into the district with Israeli flags
before being stopped by police.
   Israel radio said armed Kach members circulated through the Old
City and police said two were arrested. The Kach movement, headed
by U.S.-born Rabbi Meir Kahane, calls for the ouster of Arabs from
Israeli-held territory.
   Few tourists visited the Old City and other sections of east
Jerusalem.
   ``There is a tremendous police presence here, and we are a
little worried about getting caught in something,'' said Tom
McNeely, a 47-year-old lawyer from Charlotte, N.C., as he and his
wife walked along Jerusalem's Via Dolorosa.
</TEXT>
