<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Police,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gujarat State Police Replaced By Army And Paramilitary Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gujarat state's 59,000-member police
force has been disarmed following a union dispute and was replaced
Sunday by army and federal paramilitary troops, government
television reported.
   It said 54 policemen were dismissed for ``high indiscipline''
and an unspecified number of other officers were arrested for
indiscipline or criminal activities.
   Among those arrested was Ashok Bhatt, the leader of one of the
western state's seven police unions, according to the report. It
said four of the unions, including Bhatt's, were ordered disbanded
and the police force ``has been disarmed.''
   The United News of India and the Press Trust of India news
agencies said the army was officially activated late Sunday in the
industrial city of Ahmedabad, 18 miles south of the state capital
of Gandhinagar.
   They reported paramilitary police were deployed in other major
cities in Gujarat and ordered to take control of all of the police
armories.
   UNI said about 3,000 dismissed policemen and their supporters
gathered in Ahmedabad, a city of nearly 2 million people, to
protest the action by the federal government in New Delhi.
   It said paramilitary units using wooden staves and tear gas
dispersed the crowd and two people suffered minor injuries during
scuffles.
   Bhatt has been accused of making speeches critical of President
Ramaswami Venkataraman.
   The Press Trust of India also said he had urged Gujarat state's
reserve policemen to refuse temporary duty in Punjab, the northern
state where militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland since 1982.
   Both news agencies said army troops held ceremonial ``flag
marches'' in several major cities, including Ahmedabad, to display
their presence.
   Gujarat's chief minister, Amarsinh Chaudhary, took the action
against the police unions two days after returning from talks with
federal officials in New Delhi.
   He was quoted by the Press Trust of India as saying that he
moved against police ``errors'' and said most of India's 22 states
are opposed to police unions.
   India has a federal form of government, with the states having
their own governments led by a chief minister and police forces,
but the central government has overiding authority.
</TEXT>
