<HEAD>Reports Says Judge May Have Been Target of Fatal Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British news agency said
Sunday that a judge whose home was attacked last year may have been
the target of an Irish Republican Army bomb that killed three
people.
   The Press Association said sources, whom it did not identify,
believed the IRA's attack Saturday was meant for Judge Ian Higgins
of north Belfast, one of two Roman Catholic high court judges in
Northern Ireland.
   Police declined to comment on the report, which the news agency
attributed to sources in Belfast and Dublin, in the Republic of
Ireland.
   Higgins was returning with his wife and daughter from a vacation
in the United States.
   The IRA said it accidentally set off a bomb killing Robert James
Hanna of Hillsborough, his wife, and their 6-year-old child. The
family from Northern Ireland was also returning from a U.S. trip.
   The outlawed group, fighting to end British rule in Northern
Ireland, said the bomb detonated prematurely. But it said earlier
the attack was meant for British soldiers.
   In February 1987, Higgins' home in Belfast was hit with gunfire
and rockets. Higgins escaped injury.
   He arrived at Dublin Airport on Saturday morning and was
traveling under Irish police escort on the same road to Belfast
where the explosion occurred. But he and his family reached the
border about a half hour after the explosion near Newry, about a
mile into Northern Ireland, blew up the Hanna's vehicle.
   Authorities said they did not know where the judge and his
family or the Hannas had been vacationing in the United States.
</TEXT>
