<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TaiwanDissident     07-24 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan Dissident,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Battle Police At Airport, Two Reporters Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and an estimated 1,000 supporters
of an opposition politican battled at Taiwan's airport Sunday after
authorities refused entry to an exiled dissident who seeks
independence for Taiwan.
   Officials said two reporters were hospitalized with head
injuries after they were attacked by people in the crowd who
apparently thought the journalists were plainclothes policemen. No
other casualties were reported.
   Police said Chen Wan-chen, 38, who has lived in the United
States since 1979 and owns a bookstore in Los Angeles, tried to
enter Taiwan aboard a Singapore Airlines flight from the United
States but was detected and forced to leave on the same plane en
route to Singapore.
   They said Ms. Chen was denied entry because she might endanger
Taiwan's internal security and she did not have an entry visa.
   The crowd had gathered at Chiang Kai-shek International Airport,
31 miles west of Taipei, for the arrival of Hung Chi-chang, a
leader of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party who had
visited the Philippines and the United States.
   Party officials said Hung's supporters wanted to protect him
from possible arrest. Authorities have accused Hung of being
involved in an anti-government demonstration last May in which
about 200 people were injured.
   Ms. Chen, wearing a wig and using an altered Taiwan passport,
was on the same flight as Hung, but Hung and officials of his party
said they did not know she was aboard. When reports spread at the
airport that Ms. Chen would not be allowed to enter the country,
people in the crowd became angry and attacked police, officials
said.
   The Nationalist Chinese established their government in Taiwan
after they were defeated in 1949 in China's civil war by the
Communists.
   The Communists claim Taiwan is a Chinese province and both they
and the Nationalists are opposed to an independent Taiwan.
</TEXT>
