<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0754 07-24 0948</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0754,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bentsen In Inaugural Campaign Swing; Bush Targets Female
Voters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 25-26 to UPDATE with Dukakis back in Boston,
Bentsen in Washington. Picks up 27th graf pvs, bgng: Treasury
Secretary</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush wooed women voters Sunday with an
ambitious child-care proposal, as yet another poll pointed up his
need to close the ``gender gap.'' And Democrat Michael Dukakis with
his running mate Lloyd Bentsen wrapped up their first campaign
swing as political partners.
   Both presidential contenders faced some vocal opposition on the
campaign trail.
   Bush won praise for a $2.2 billion child-care plan he unveiled
before a group of professional women. But when he finished
speaking, many in the audience broke into chants of ``E-R-A'' _ a
reference to the Equal Rights Amendment, which the vice president
opposes.
   And Dukakis, who supports abortion rights, was heckled by
anti-abortion protesters in St. Louis, where he attended church
services.
   The Democrats, meanwhile, were looking back with satisfaction on
their national convention, which ended last week, while the
Republicans looked ahead to theirs, three weeks away.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters aboard Air
Force One en route to Washington on Sunday that President Reagan
may make a Midwestern campaign trip on Bush's behalf between now
and the convention.
   Bush's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, promised at least one
piece of GOP convention drama, pledging that the vice president
would not unveil his choice of a running mate until next month in
New Orleans.
   ``He's going to keep his own counsel on it, and he's going to
let us all know at the convention,'' Atwater said Sunday in an
interview on CBS' ``Face The Nation.''
   ``I think that will be very exciting and very dramatic,'' he
said.
   The Republicans say their convention preparations are proceeding
on schedule, but local fund-raisers in New Orleans acknowledged
they would have to work hard to hunt up the cash for facilities and
services the city has promised to provide during the gathering.
   Ron Jones, heading up the convention city's fund drive, said
fund raising was running ``maybe a little behind'' but that the
money should be on hand before the convention opens Aug. 15.
   Republicans and Democrats were united in one respect _ the
amount of time they were devoting to talk of party unity.
   Pat Robertson, Bush's onetime rival for the GOP nomination,
urged his supporters to rally behind the vice president. The
television evangelist also said his flock wasn't out to start any
floor fights at the Republican convention.
   However, Robertson told a Republican rally in Charleston, S.C.
on Saturday that he would like to see a plank calling for the
nomination of conservative candidates at all levels of the federal
judiciary.
   The Democrats, meanwhile, were giving themselves good reviews.
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Democrats came out of their
convention well positioned for a big win in the fall.
   ``It will be one of the great defeats in modern history for the
Republicans,'' Cuomo said Sunday on ``Face the Nation.'' The
governor, who got more attention as a non-candidate than some of
the Democratic candidates did, said he would campaign for Dukakis
``wherever he wants me.''
   As for the candidates themselves, Bush was accompanied by former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole as he addressed the
National Convention of Business and Professional Women's Clubs in
Albuquerque on Sunday. His child-care proposal was favorably
received by the group.
   The proposal, initially affecting only low-income families,
would eventually apply to all families with children under age 4 in
which at least one parent worked, he said.
   ``This is one of his first concrete gestures'' toward women, the
group's president, Beth Wray, said afterward.
   A number of surveys have suggested that Dukakis is better
regarded by female voters than is Bush. The latest poll, by
Newsweek magazine, said Bush trailed Dukakis by 17 points overall _
55 percent to 38 percent _ and that Dukakis' strength was due in
part to the backing of 58 percent of the female voters.
   The survey of 948 registered voters, conducted July 21-22, had a
margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   Dukakis, attending Sunday church services with Bentsen in St.
Louis, faced anti-abortion protesters outside. The governor calls
abortion a ``difficult, very serious, very important ethical and
moral judgment'' that a woman must make for herself.
   In St. Louis, Dukakis and Bentsen were introduced by Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who had also sought the Democratic
nomination.
   The Democratic nominee and his running mate got off to a running
start after the convention that anointed them. They visited five
states, including the big battlegrounds of California and Texas.
   Dukakis returned to Boston on Sunday night, where he was
welcomed by about 150 people at Logan International Airport.
Bentsen, meanwhile, flew back to Washington.
   Bush returned to Washington on Sunday night after a five-day
campaign swing that took him to eight states.
   Treasury Secretary James Baker, who was in California for a
weekend fund-raising event, accompanied Reagan on his return flight
from California on Sunday, but an administration official dismissed
speculation that Baker's presence signaled any immediate
announcement of his resignation to run the Bush campaign.
   Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, Baker had ``a very brief
chat'' with Reagan and added: ``He's still treasury secretary, put
it that way.''
   When reporters aboard the plane sent Baker a note asking them to
come back and talk to him about the matter, he replied with a note
with a folder that contained a dollar bill.
   ``Please note the title under the signature,'' Baker wrote. That
title, of course, is secretary of the treasury.
</TEXT>
