<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Soviets     07-24 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Leaders Hail Consular Mission To Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Sunday that
he hopes the ``historic mission'' of a six-member Israeli
delegation to Moscow would lead to the resumption of Israeli-Soviet
ties severed in 1967.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said the trip would be a landmark
in Israeli-Soviet relations.
   Shamir heads the conservative Likud bloc and Peres the socialist
Labor Party. The fractious coalition has governed Israel since 1984
when neither party gained a majority in the election.
   Shamir and Peres conducted separate briefings for the consular
group that will leave Tuesday for the Netherlands. The delegates
are to receive Soviet visas at The Hague on Wednesday and depart
for Moscow the next day. The Netherlands represents Israeli
interests in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union cut diplomatic relations with the Jewish state
after the 1967 Middle East War.
   Shamir aide Avi Pazner quoted the prime minister as saying he
hoped the ``historic mission ... would lead to the process of
normalization in the Israeli-Soviet relations.''
   It will be the first visit to the Soviet Union by an official
Israeli diplomatic group to Moscow in more than 20 years.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said Peres discussed with
the delegates the political changes initiated by Soviet leader
Mikail S. Gorbachev and noted that the Kremlin has recently allowed
thousands of Soviet Jews to visit their relatives in Israel.
   Liel reported Peres said there are as many as 2,000 Soviet
Jewish visitors now in Israel.
   The Kremlin has allowed increased Jewish emigration, with 1,470
Soviet Jews permitted to leave in June _ the sixth straight rise in
the monthly total.
   According to the Geneva-based Intergovernmental Committee for
Migration, a total of 6,017 Soviet Jews have emigrated this year
compared to 8,011 during all of 1987.
   Last year an eight-member Soviet consular delegation visited
Israel to survey Russian property and meet with Soviet citizens
living in Israel. Israel allowed the visit on condition that the
Soviets reciprocate.
   The Soviet group is still in Israel. Despite its limited task,
Israeli officials have expressed hope it would become a permanent
mission.
   Israel radio said the Israeli group going to Moscow is headed by
diplomat Meron Gordon.
</TEXT>
