<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Storm     07-24 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Storm,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hailstorm, Flooding Kill 54 in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains accompanied by hail flooded wide
areas of northwestern China, collapsing thousands of homes and
killing 54 people, an official report said Sunday.
   The storm was the latest in a series of weather disasters in
China that have claimed nearly 600 lives in the past week.
   Up to 5.6 inches of rain fell in just over two hours Saturday in
three counties of Gansu province, the Xinhua News Agency said.
   It reported that large areas of farmland were flooded and
thousands of mud houses and cave homes, typical to the region,
collapsed.
   The brief report did not say if the reported victims were killed
by the collapsing homes.
   In Xifeng City, one of the hardest-hit areas, 730 homes
collapsed and shops and warehouses were flooded, Xinhua said.
   Twenty deaths were reported from Typhoon Warren, which swept
into southeastern Guangdong province on Tuesday with winds of up to
80 mph.
   Meanwhile, a drought and heat wave in central China have claimed
nearly 500 lives.
</TEXT>
