<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SealProtest     07-24 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Seal Protest,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Form Human Chain to Protest Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLAND, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 40,000
demonstrators formed a 24-mile human chain across a North Sea
island Sunday to protest pollution they blame for killing thousands
of seals.
   The human chain across Sylt, off West Germany's northern state
of Schleswig-Holstein, formed for 15 minutes.
   Speaking later at a demonstration at the Sylt resort community
of Westerland, Schleswig-Holstein Environment Minister Berndt
Heydemann called for stepped-up efforts to protect the North Sea.
   Other demonstrations against North Sea pollution were also held
Sunday in his state.
   Environmentalists blame pollution for a virus that in recent
months killed more than 15,000 seals off Denmark, Sweden, West
Germany and the Netherlands.
   However, many scientists doubt that theory, since waters where
many seals have died are relatively free of pollution.
</TEXT>
