<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--CemeteryWalkout     07-24 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cemetery Walkout,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Cemetery Workers in San Francisco Area Approve Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking workers at 10 San Francisco Bay
area cemeteries said Sunday they would return to work Monday after
accepting an agreement worked out with graveyard owners over the
weekend.
   Up to 800 bodies have been kept in storage because of the
strike, which began May 30.
   Members of the cemetery workers' Local 265 approved a proposed
three-year contract by a 2-1 ratio during voting early Sunday.
   Among other things, the new pact restricts subcontracting. Local
265 President Jose Valdez said that workers will not lose jobs they
previously performed, but subcontractors will perform jobs that
union workers don't have the proper machinery to perform or haven't
done in the past.
   Valdez would not disclose the number of union members voting on
the contract, except to say that ``most of the people were there to
vote.''
</TEXT>
