<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomosexualTeachers     07-24 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homosexual Teachers,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Teachers Urged to Speak Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homosexual teachers should declare their sexual
preference openly and confront those who would drive them from the
public schools, speakers said Sunday at a conference of gay
instructors.
   ``The time is right for us to assert ourselves in the
educational field,'' said Virginia Uribe, a Los Angeles high school
teacher. ``We have so much power if we come out, and we have so
little power if we're not out.''
   That message, coming near the conclusion of Uribe's keynote
address, drew tumultuous applause from about 75 elementary, high
school and college educators at the daylong conference, held in
conjunction with a weeklong Lesbian and Gay Health Conference and
AIDS Forum.
   Other speakers echoed the message of openness, but afterward,
when the group divided into small workshops, boldness gave way to
caution.
   ``To some of us, this is not real,'' said a teacher from a
Kansas elementary school district who didn't want her name
published. ``I'd love to tell my kids that I'm a lesbian, but if I
did, I wouldn't be there Monday.''
   When a young teacher from Ohio asked for advice on whether he
should declare his homosexuality right away or wait until he had
obtained tenure, the answer came in a chorus: ``Get tenure.''
   Warren Blumenfeld, a teacher in the Watertown, Mass., schools,
said he became a better teacher after he disclosed his sexual
orientation.
   ``When I first got out of ed school, I thought I wouldn't say
anything to my students about it,'' he recalled. ``But that drained
me of my energy. When I came out it freed me up to be who I was and
to channel my energy into constructive channels.''
   However, Blumenfeld also cited a 1982 Gallup poll indicating
that 59 percent of Americans felt homosexual educators should be
excluded from public schools.
   The educators were united in asserting that they pose no danger
to students and, in fact, can serve as positive role models.
   ``Homosexuality is not contagious,'' said Blumenfeld. ``Having
an openly gay or lesbian teacher will not make students who are
confused become gay or lesbian.
   ``But what it will do is it will show them that the option is
OK, and if they happen to be gay, it will reduce their isolation.''
</TEXT>
