<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AlabamaBusWreck 3rdLd-Writethru a0790 07-24 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alabama Bus Wreck, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0790,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Killed, 34 Injured When Bus Overturns in Alabama</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf `A spokesman ...' to UPDATE with identity of
dead woman. Picks up 4th graf, `The bus ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An intercity bus veered off a road
apparently to avoid a collision and overturned in a rural area
Sunday, killing a woman and injuring all 34 others aboard,
authorities said.
   A car apparently was traveling in the wrong lane of the two-lane
highway at the time of the accident, Camden Police Chief John
Rogers said. He said the bus driver, who was among those injured,
swerved off the road to avoid a collision and the other car did not
stop.
   Rosie Gulley, 68, of New York City was killed, said state police
Capt. George Jones in Selma. A spokesman at St. Margaret's Hospital
in Montgomery said the passenger died after being flown there by
helicopter.
   The bus, operated by Mobile-based Colonial Trailways, was
carrying 34 passengers and the driver, state police spokesman Will
Rogers said.
   Frank Smith, supervisor of operations for the 53-year-old
company, said, ``We had some serious injuries. Three or four
(passengers) were transferred to Montgomery,'' the nearest major
city to the isolated area east of the Alabama River where the
accident occurred.
   Some of the passengers suffered chest injuries and at least two
women will require dental treatment, said Arden Chesnut,
administrator of J. Paul Jones Hospital in Camden. She said most of
the injured were treated and released Sunday afternoon.
   Troopers said the accident occurred on Alabama Route 265 about
three miles south of Camden and some 130 miles north of Mobile.
   Smith said the bus was headed from Mobile to New York, and his
company, which operates routes in Alabama and three other states,
was handling the Mobile-Montgomery portion.
   It was the company's first fatal accident, Smith said.
</TEXT>
