<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Clements, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0730,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Governor Released from Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs for 2nd graf to UPDATE with Clements' comments
to reporters after release from hospital. Picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`The governor's ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements was released Sunday
after being hospitalized for five nights following a mild stroke
and said he felt good enough to campaign vigorously for George Bush
for president.
   Asked if his illness had given him a new perspective on life,
the 71-year-old Republican said, ``My perspective hasn't changed
one iota _ beat Dukakis.''
   Clements told reporters in the hospital lobby that he felt
great, adding: ``I don't anticipate that I'm going to curtail my
activities at all. I'll continue to play tennis, I'll continue to
go out to Taos (his vacation home in New Mexico) _ which has a high
altitude _ for vacation periods, I'll continue to have a full
schedule so far as the governor's office is concerned.''
   An attending physician said Clements, was ``in excellent
condition,'' according to Cheryl McEntire, spokeswoman for Seton
Medical Center.
   The governor's release, originally scheduled for Saturday, was
delayed on doctors' orders after they detected a slight
irregularity in Clements' heart rhythm.
   Clements admitted himself to Seton Medical Center on Tuesday
after consulting a physician about a vision problem.
   Dr. David Morris, a heart specialist, and Dr. Jerry Tindel, a
neurologist, said tests indicated that Clements was suffering from
a slight heartbeat irregularity.
   The condition could have caused a tiny blood clot to form in his
heart and pass into his brain, causing the stroke, the doctors said.
   Asked how long it would take for the governor to resume a normal
work day, Clements press secretary Reggie Bashur said, ``Dr. Morris
has indicated it's a matter of several days to a week ....''
   Bashur said doctors had indicated Clements would be ``on some
form of medication for the heart rhythm for an indefinite period of
time.''
</TEXT>
