<HEAD>Archbishop Returns to Cincinnati for Treatment of Stroke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Daniel Pilarczyk
returned Sunday night to a Cincinnati hospital where he was to
undergo surgery to repair a ruptured aneurysm at the base of his
brain, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Pilarczyk, 53, head of the Cincinnati archdiocese, suffered a
stroke Saturday while vacationing in Gatlinburg, Tenn. He was taken
to the University of Tennessee Medical Center for treatment, then
transported by helicopter to Good Samaritan Hospital in Cincinnati.
   ``He arrived conscious and in good spirits,'' spokeswoman Kathy
Clark said. She said the surgery, scheduled for Monday, is expected
to last about 5{ hours.
   ``He has an excellent medical history, and they're anticipating
everything will go smoothly,'' Ms. Clark said.
   An aneurism is a sac formed by the enlargement of a weakened
blood vessel wall.
   Pilarczyk was listed in serious condition Sunday night.
   Archdiocese spokesman Ray George said Pilarczyk recognized
friends and family members who visited him at the Tennessee
hospital. Pilarczyk had been vacationing about a week when he
became ill.
