<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0787,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Urges Peace Over Politics at Cambodian Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Talks open, new info-changes grafs 1-9. Pick up 9th graf pvs:
The informal...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the warring factions in
Cambodia opened informal talks Monday at the presidential palace in
Bogor and Indonesian officials called it a ``coffee morning.''
   No name plates or other identification labels were on the
circular table where delegates from Cambodia and an alliance of
Cambodian resistance groups began negotiations in Bogor, 40 miles
south of Jakarta, to end the bloody conflict.
   One of the rebel leaders on Sunday urged the other delegates to
put aside politics, and then he knelt in prayer before three
Buddhist monks.
   ``I believe strongly in this meeting as the best chance for a
solution to the Cambodian problem,'' Son Sann, a former Cambodian
premier, told reporters at the airport following his arrival.
   The peace talks, hosted by Indonesia, mark the first time the
rebels have sat down face-to-face with government leaders since
Vietnam invaded Cambodia nearly 10 years ago.
   Son Sann said the talks represented a chance for the parties
involved ``not to think about political things, but only one thing:
To put an end to the suffering of the Cambodian people. If everyone
thinks about that, then we will have good results.''
   Since 1970, Cambodia has suffered a devastating five-year civil
war, a reign of terror by the Chinese-backed communist Khmer Rouge
from 1975 to 1978, a 1978 Vietnamese invasion and a continuing
guerrilla war against the Vietnamese-backed government. Millions of
people have been killed in the nation's turmoil.
   The heads of Cambodia's three rebel factions arrived Sunday in
Indonesia.
   If the talk's make progress, officials from Vietnam, Laos and
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations were to join in
Wednesday.
   The informal, phased nature of the talks has been labeled
``cocktail party'' diplomacy.
   Indonesia's foreign minister, Ali Alatas, greeted the heads of
the three guerrilla groups on Sunday. They were Son Sann, head of
the Khmer People's National Liberation Front; Khieu Samphan of the
Khmer Rouge, and Prince Norodom Ranariddh. He was representing his
father, Prince Norodom Sihanouk, who quit the resistance leadership
but remains perhaps the most popular figure in Cambodia.
   Their adversaries _ Vietnam's Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach
and the prime minister of Cambodia's government, Hun Sen _ arrived
in Jakarta Saturday.
   Vietnam has announced it will withdraw 50,000 troops, or about
half its force in Cambodia, this year and the rest by early 1990.
   Son Sann said Sunday that he had asked Alatas and Malaysia's
prime minister, Mahathir Mohammed, to ask people to pray for
success of the talks in all mosques in their Moslem nations. He
said he had also asked Pope John Paul II to encourage prayers in
Roman Catholic churches worldwide.
   He then knelt on the floor of the airport's VIP lounge, closed
his eyes, and folded his hands to his forehead in prayer before
three Buddhist monks, who chanted blessings. The monks came from
the United States, Canada and France to bless participants in the
talks.
   Though Son Sann and Sihanouk are allied with the communist Khmer
Rouge in a resistance coalition, they strongly distrust the group
because it killed hundreds of thousands of people when it ruled
Cambodia from 1975 until Vietnam invaded.
   Sihanouk resigned as president of the coalition earlier this
month because he said Khmer Rouge forces were killing his men.
   The prince, who ruled Cambodia for three decades, arrived
Saturday in Jakarta as a guest of Indonesian President Suharto, but
he said he would not attend the talks personally.
   In a recent interview with Indonesian media, Alatas said all
factions agreed that Sihanouk would lead a future Cambodia.
</TEXT>
