<1ST_LINE>d f AM-ControlData     07-24 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Control Data,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Company To Shut Down Some Plants Temporarily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp., faced with
slower-than-expected U.S. sales of mainframe computers, plans to
shut down several plants temporarily and idle 7 percent of its work
force the last week in August.
   The move will affect about 2,000 workers in St. Louis Park,
Plymouth and Arden Hills and about 500 employees in Sunnyvale,
Calif., and Kansas City, Mo., said Tom Charland, a spokesman for
the Computer Products Division, which makes mainframe computers.
   Employees will have a choice of taking accrued paid vacation
during that week, or going without pay, Charland said Friday. Other
divisions will not be affected by the shutdown, he said.
   The move will help consolidate vacation expenses in the third
quarter, which will improve cash flow in the fourth quarter ``when
we want to do well,' Charland said. ``It's hard to say what that
means, because so much of our business is concentrated at the end
of the year.''
   Control Data has closed some of its operations temporarily
before, but this is the first time it has done so this year,
Charland said. The most recent shutdown occurred last year in the
Government Systems Group, which makes military computers, he said.
</TEXT>
